n[[Category:Timelines of current events]]\n", "text_old": "{{see also|2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries#Timeline|2020 Republican Party presidential primaries#Timeline}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = Timeline of the 2020 United States presidential election\n| country = USA\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = Timeline of the 2016 United States presidential election\n| previous_year = 2016\n| next_election = Timeline of the 2024 United States presidential election\n| next_year = 2024\n}}\n{{US 2020 presidential elections series}}\nThe following is a '''timeline of major events''' leading up, during, and after the United States presidential election of 2020. President [[Donald Trump]] of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], who was elected in [[2016 United States presidential election|2016]], is seeking reelection to a second term.\n\nThe [[2020 United States presidential election|election]] is the 59th [[quadrennial]] [[United States presidential election]] and is scheduled to be held on November 3, 2020. The [[United States presidential primary|presidential primaries and caucuses]] are scheduled to be held between February and June 2020, staggered among the 50 states, [[Washington, D.C.]], and U.S. territories. The [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] is scheduled to certify the electoral result on January 5, 2021, and the new or incumbent president and vice president will be [[United States presidential inauguration|inaugurated]] on January 20, 2021.\n\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n== 2017 ==\n[[File:John Delaney (46743402692).jpg|thumb|[[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]] was the first major Democratic candidate to announce his campaign on July 28, 2017]]\n\n*'''February 17''': Republican incumbent president [[Donald Trump]] informally announces his candidacy for a second term and holds the first of a series of occasional reelection campaign rallies in [[Melbourne, Florida]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Superville|first1=Darlene|last2=Riechmann|first2=Deb|title=Outside of Washington, Trump slips back into campaign mode|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2017/02/18/outside-washington-trump-slips-back-into-campaign-mode.html|website=Fox News|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=March 5, 2017|location=West Palm Beach, Florida|date=February 18, 2017}}</ref>\n*'''July 28''': Representative [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]] of Maryland officially announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/politics/blog/bs-md-delaney-announcement-20170728-story.html |title=Delaney announces campaign for president, becomes first to challenge Trump |work=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |date=July 28, 2017 |accessdate=December 11, 2018 |first=John |last=Fritze}}</ref> breaking the record for the earliest official presidential candidacy declaration in history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailykos.com/story/2017/7/29/1685409/-John-Delaney-s-Presidential-Campaign-Announcement-is-the-Earliest-in-History|title=John Delaney's Presidential Campaign Announcement is the Earliest in History|website=Daily Kos|access-date=August 3, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''November 6''': Tech entrepreneur [[Andrew Yang]] of [[New York (state)|New York]] announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/03/politics/2020-dem-announcements/index.html|title=Here's how 2020 Democrats announced their campaigns |work=[[CNN]]|date=February 13, 2019| first=Schwarz|last= Hunter}}</ref>\n\n== 2018 ==\n*'''January 16''': Anti-war activist [[Adam Kokesh]] announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Libertarian Party. Hours after the announcement, he was pulled over twice and subsequently arrested on [[drug possession|possession]]-related charges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/2018/01/20/hours-after-declaring-candidacy-presidential-hopeful-arrested-in-wise-county/|title=Hours after declaring candidacy, presidential hopeful arrested in Wise County|date=January 19, 2018|author=Ramirez, Marc|accessdate=October 6, 2019|work=[[The Dallas Morning News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.star-telegram.com/news/local/fort-worth/article195357574.html|title=He announced his candidacy for president. 30 minutes later, he was arrested|author=Hanna, Bill|date=January 18, 2018|accessdate=October 6, 2019|work=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]}}</ref>\n*'''May 3''': The [[Republican National Committee]] eliminates their debate committee for the 2020 election cycle, signaling that that they do not plan to sanction any debates between Trump and possible primary challengers.<ref>{{cite new |title=Republican Party nixes debate committee ahead of 2020|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/05/03/politics/rnc-2020-debates/index.html|last=Berg |first=Rebecca|publisher=CNN|date=May 3, 2018}}</ref>\n*'''July 3''': Former [[Libertarian National Committee]] vice-chair [[Arvin Vohra]] announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Libertarian Party.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://reason.com/2018/07/06/controversialist-arvin-vohra-announces-2/|title=Controversialist Arvin Vohra Announces 2020 Libertarian Presidential Run|author=Welch, Matt|date=July 6, 2018|accessdate=October 6, 2019|work=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]}}</ref>\n*'''July 18''': [[Charlotte, North Carolina]] is chosen as the host city of the [[2020 Republican National Convention]]<ref name=\"RNC-Charlotte\">{{cite web|url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/news/politics-government/rnc-2020/article215204290.html|title=GOP picks Charlotte for 2020 convention. Now, the fundraising and organizing begin.|date=July 20, 2018|first=Jim|last=Morill|work=[[The Charlotte Observer]]|accessdate=July 24, 2018}}</ref>\n*'''August 25''': Democratic Party officials and television networks begin discussions as to the nature and scheduling of the following year's debates and the nomination process.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.apnews.com/5068444bc8d549229b1c2b8fb079055b|title=APNewsBreak: DNC, TV networks discuss presidential debates|date=August 25, 2018|publisher=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> Changes were made to the role of [[superdelegate]]s, deciding to only allow them to vote on the first ballot if the nomination is uncontested<ref name=\"superdelegates\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2018/03/10/dnc-advances-changes-presidential-nominating-process/413876002/|title=DNC advances changes to presidential nominating process|work=USA TODAY|access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref>\n*'''November 6''': In the [[2018 United States elections|midterm elections]], the Democrats capture control of the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] with a net gain of 41 seats. The Republicans hold their majority in the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] with a net gain of two seats.<ref name=\"skelleysenate\">{{cite news |last=Skelley |first=Geoffrey |title=Why Did The House Get Bluer And The Senate Get Redder? |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/why-did-the-house-get-bluer-and-the-senate-get-redder/ |accessdate=November 16, 2018 |publisher=FiveThirtyEight |date=November 16, 2018}}</ref>     \n*'''November 7''': President Trump confirms that [[Mike Pence]] will remain vice presidential pick<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-pence-idUSKCN1NC2HU|title=Trump says Pence to be his running mate in 2020|date=November 7, 2018|work=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n*'''November 11''': West Virginia state senator [[Richard Ojeda]] announces candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party. He ultimately would become the first candidate to withdraw from the race, suspending his campaign on January 25, 2019, more than a year before the Iowa caucus ''(see below)''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsaz.com/content/news/State-Senator-Richard-Ojeda-to-run-for-President-in-2020-500248782.html |title=State Senator Richard Ojeda to run for President in 2020 |author=WSAZ News Staff |date=November 11, 2018 |publisher=[[WSAZ-TV]] |location=Huntington, West Virginia |access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref>\n*'''December 12''': Former secretary of housing and urban development [[Julian Castro]] forms a presidential exploratory committee for a possible run for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref name=\"bloomberg\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-12-12/urgent-apnewsbreak-julian-castro-moves-toward-2020-white-house-run|title=Julian Castro Forming Presidential Exploratory Committee|last=Weber|first=Paul|date=December 12, 2018|accessdate=December 12, 2018|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n*'''December 31''': Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]] of Massachusetts forms an exploratory committee for a possible run for the nomination of the Democratic Party.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/31/politics/elizabeth-warren-exploratory-committee-2020/index.html |title=Elizabeth Warren launches exploratory committee ahead of likely 2020 presidential run |first1=MJ |last1=Lee |first2=Gregory |last2=Krieg |date=December 31, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=December 31, 2018}}</ref> She would ultimately decide to commit to an official campaign in February 2019 ''(see below)''.\n\n== 2019 ==\n=== January 2019 ===\n[[File:Kamala Harris announcing her candidacy for presidency.png|thumb|[[Kamala Harris]] launched her campaign on January 21, 2019]]\n\n*'''January 11''': Representative [[Tulsi Gabbard]] of Hawaii announces she has decided to run for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/11/politics/tulsi-gabbard-van-jones/index.html|title=Tulsi Gabbard says she will run for president in 2020|last=Kelly|first=Caroline|date=January 11, 2019|website=Cnn.com|language=en-US|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''January 12''': Former [[Secretary of Housing and Urban Development|secretary of housing and urban development]] [[Julian Castro]] officially announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref name=\"bloomberg\" /><ref>{{Citation|last=NBC News|title=Watch Live: Juli\u00e1n Castro to make 2020 presidential campaign announcement|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cECfx0xrPwU|access-date=January 12, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''January 15''': Senator [[Kirsten Gillibrand]] of New York announces the formation of an exploratory committee for a possible run for the nomination of the Democratic Party.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/15/us/politics/gillibrand-president-election.html|title=Kirsten Gillibrand, New York Senator, Joins Democratic Race for President|last=Goldmacher|first=Shane|date=January 15, 2019|website=Nytimes.com}}</ref> She would then launch an official campaign in March ''(see below)''.\n*'''January 21''': Senator [[Kamala Harris]] of California officially announces her candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref name=\"harris announcement\">{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/beta-story-container/Politics/sen-kamala-harris-announces-run-president-2020/story?id=60472358|title=Sen. Kamala Harris announces she will run for president in 2020|date=January 21, 2019|first=Adam|last=Kelsey|work=[[ABC News]]}}</ref>\n*'''January 23''': [[List of mayors of South Bend, Indiana|Mayor]] of [[South Bend, Indiana]], [[Pete Buttigieg]] announces the formation of an exploratory committee for a possible run for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref name=\"Buttigieg-exploratory\">{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/beta-story-container/Politics/south-bend-mayor-pete-buttigieg-announces-presidential-exploratory/story?id=60543998|title=South Bend Mayor Pete Buttigieg launches presidential exploratory committee, could be nation's first openly gay nominee|work=[[ABC News]]|access-date=2019-01-23}}</ref>\n*'''January 25''':\n** Ojeda drops out of the Democratic nomination race, saying that he has little chance of success.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rodrigo|first=Chris|title=Dem Richard Ojeda drops out of presidential race|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/427009-ojeda-drops-out-of-presidential-race|date=January 25, 2019|accessdate=January 25, 2019|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]}}</ref>\n** The [[Republican National Committee]] unofficially endorses Trump.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/republican-party-to-express-undivided-support-for-trump/4756108.html|title=Republican Party to Express 'Undivided Support' for Trump|website=VOA}}</ref>\n*'''January 27:''' [[Starbucks]] founder [[Howard Schultz]] announces possible independent presidential bid,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/democrats-are-uneasy-howard-schultzs-potential-presidential-bid-1179776|title=Former Starbucks Chairman Howard Schultz Announces Potential Presidential Bid on '60 Minutes'|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> which is followed by a furious backlash on social media<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eater.com/2019/1/28/18201052/howard-schultz-president-2020-independent-candidate|title=Running Starbucks Doesn\u2019t Mean You Should Run for President|first=Whitney|last=Filloon|date=January 28, 2019|website=Eater.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2019/01/howard-schultz-backlash-presidential-campaign/|title=Howard Schultz tried to deflect criticism of his presidential flirtation. He only made things worse.|website=Motherjones.com}}</ref>\n*'''January 28''': Spiritual teacher and author [[Marianne Williamson]] of California announces her candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/margiewarrell/2019/01/29/marianne-williamson-can-love-transcend-fear/#3d1050ea141b|title=Marianne Williamson: Can A Presidential Bid Fueled By Love Transcend The Politics Of Fear?|last=Warrell|first=Margie|date=January 29, 2019|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=January 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== February 2019 ===\n[[File:Bill Weld announcing (02).png|thumb|[[Bill Weld]] announcing the formation of an exploratory committee on February 15, 2019, becoming Trump's first official Republican challenger]]\n\n*'''February 1:''' On [[Twitter]], Senator [[Cory Booker]] of New Jersey announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/sen-cory-booker-of-new-jersey-launches-presidential-campaign-11549022453|title=Sen. Cory Booker of New Jersey Launches Presidential Campaign|first=Ken|last=Thomas|date=February 1, 2019|accessdate=February 1, 2019|website=Wsj.com}}</ref>\n*'''February 9''': Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]] of Massachusetts announces her candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party, soon after forming an exploratory committee.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-elizabeth-warren-20190209-story.html|title=Elizabeth Warren officially kicks off bid for White House|agency=Associated Press|access-date=February 9, 2019|date=February 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''February 10:''' Senator [[Amy Klobuchar]] of Minnesota announces her candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref name=\"klobuchar announcement\">{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/2/10/18136170/amy-klobuchar-running-president-announcement|title=Sen. Amy Klobuchar has won every one of her elections by huge margins. Now she\u2019s running for president.|first=Tara|last=Golshan|publisher=Vox}}</ref>\n*'''February 12:''' The first mass-rally of the Trump campaign of the year takes place in [[El Paso]], Texas. A counter-rally led by former Democratic U.S. representative [[Beto O'Rourke]] of Texas takes place less than a mile away.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/12/politics/donald-trump-el-paso-beto-orourke/index.html|title=The 50 most eye-popping lines from Donald Trump's El Paso speech|first=Chris|last=Cillizza|website=Cnn.com}}</ref> O\u2019Rourke would later enter the race in March for the Democratic nomination ''(see below)''.\n* '''February 13\u201315:''' Winter meeting of the Democratic National Committee, in which the rules of the upcoming primary are promulgated<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2019-02-13/dnc-chair-2-stages-16-spots-for-first-2-democratic-debates|title=DNC Chair: Qualifications for First Debates Coming This Week|website=Usnews.com|accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n*'''February 15:''' Former Massachusetts governor [[Bill Weld]] announces the formation of an exploratory committee, becoming Trump's first official challenger in the Republican primaries<ref>Battenfeld, Joe (February 15, 2019) [https://www.bostonherald.com/2019/02/15/bill-weld-launches-gop-presidential-exploratory-committee/ \"Bill Weld launches GOP presidential exploratory committee\"], ''[[Boston Herald]]''. Retrieved February 15, 2019.</ref>\n*'''February 18:''' [[Youngstown City School District|Youngstown Board of Education]] member [[Dario Hunter]] announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Green Party.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wfmj.com/story/39984258/youngstown-board-of-education-member-announces-2020-run|title=Youngstown Board of Education member announces 2020 run|date=February 19, 2019|accessdate=October 6, 2019|author=Koziol, Brandon|work=[[WFMJ-TV]]}}</ref>\n*'''February 19:''' Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] of Vermont announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bing.com/amp/s/www.usnews.com%2fnews%2fnational-news%2farticles%2f2019-02-19%2fbernie-sanders-announces-hes-running-for-president-again-in-2020%3fcontext%3damp|title=Bernie Sanders Is Running for President Again|first=Megan|last=Trimble|date=February 19, 2019|accessdate=February 19, 2019|website=Usnews.com}}</ref>\n\n=== March 2019===\n[[File:Anand Giridharadas interviews Elizabeth Warren 1, SXSW, Austin, Texas, USA (47286394562).jpg|thumb|[[Elizabeth Warren]] (right) being interviewed by [[Anand Giridharadas]] at [[South by Southwest]], March 2019]]\n\n*'''March 1''': Governor [[Jay Inslee]] of [[Washington (state)|Washington]] announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/01/politics/inslee-2020-presidential-campaign/index.html|title=Washington Gov. Jay Inslee announces 2020 presidential bid|agency=CNN|access-date=March 1, 2019|date=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''March 4''': Former governor [[John Hickenlooper]] of [[Colorado]] announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/04/us/john-hickenlooper-2020.html|title=John Hickenlooper Says He Is Running in 2020, Citing a 'Crisis of Division'|agency=New York Times|access-date=March 4, 2019|date=March 4, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''March 5''': Former mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]] of [[New York City]] announces that, after exploring the possibility, he will not run for president in 2020<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/05/us/politics/michael-bloomberg-2020.html|title=Michael Bloomberg Will Not Run for President in 2020|agency=New York Times|access-date=March 5, 2019|date=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''March 10:''' Presidential Forum at [[South by Southwest]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://politi.co/2J2HOWj|title=Politico Playbook: 2020 presidential hopefuls gather at SXSW in Austin|first1=Anna|last1=Palmer|first2=Jake|last2=Sherman|first3=Daniel|last3=Lippman|website=Politi.co|accessdate=March 14, 2019}}</ref> the first so-called \"cattle call\" event of the cycle.\n*'''March 11''': [[Milwaukee|Milwaukee, Wisconsin]] is chosen as the host city of the [[2020 Democratic National Convention]], beating out [[Miami, Florida]] and [[Houston|Houston, Texas]].<ref name=\"ABC20190311\">{{cite news | title=Milwaukee chosen as 2020 Democratic National Convention site | url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/milwaukee-chosen-2020-democratic-national-convention-site/story?id=61606127 | first=John | last=Verhovek | publisher=ABC News | date=March 11, 2019 | accessdate=March 11, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''March 13:''' [[Wayne Messam]], the Democratic mayor of [[Miramar, Florida]], announces the formation of an exploratory committee<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/433890-democratic-florida-mayor-launching-2020-presidential-exploratory-committee|title=Democratic Florida mayor launching 2020 presidential exploratory committee|first=Michael|last=Burke|date=March 13, 2019|website=Thehill.com|accessdate=March 14, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''March 14:''' O'Rourke officially announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/politics/beto-orourke-running-president-2020/|title=Beto O\u2019Rourke Confirms He\u2019s Running for President in 2020: 'This Is a Defining Moment of Truth'|website=People.com|accessdate=March 14, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''March 17:''' Gillibrand officially announces her candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/17/us/politics/gillibrand-2020-announce.html|title=Kirsten Gillibrand Officially Enters 2020 Democratic Race|first=Shane|last=Goldmacher|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 17, 2019}}</ref> having previously formed an exploratory committee two month earlier ''(see above)''.\n*'''March 28''': Messam formally announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Merica|first1=Dan|title=Florida Mayor Wayne Messam announces 2020 presidential bid|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/28/politics/wayne-messam-announces-2020-bid/index.html|publisher=CNN|date=March 28, 2019|accessdate=March 28, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''March 30''': Castro, Delaney, Klobuchar, Ryan, and Warren appear at the Heartland Forum at [[Buena Vista University]] in [[Storm Lake, Iowa]], discussing issues affecting rural Americans.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/elizabeth-warren-big-tech-807109/|title=Facebook, Amazon and Google Have a 2020 Problem|last=Kroll|first=Andy|date=March 12, 2019|website=Rolling Stone|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190318233953/https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/elizabeth-warren-big-tech-807109/|archive-date=March 18, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto20\">{{cite web|url=https://iowafarmersunion.org/heartland-forum/|title=Heartland Forum|publisher=Iowa Farmers Union|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326132245/https://iowafarmersunion.org/heartland-forum/|archive-date=March 26, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2019 ===\n[[File:Joe Biden kickoff rally May 2019.jpg|thumb|[[Joe Biden]] launched his campaign on April 25, 2019, increasing the number of major Democratic candidates to 20<ref name=\"BidenCandidacy\"/>]]\n\n* '''April 1''':  Eight Democratic candidates attend the We the People Membership Summit at the [[Warner Theatre (Washington, D.C.)|Warner Theatre]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], discussing [[Electoral reform|Democracy reform]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/20/politics/progressive-summit-2020/index.html|title=Progressive groups to host April summit with 2020 candidates|last=Saenz|first=Arlette|access-date=March 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320215117/https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/20/politics/progressive-summit-2020/index.html|archive-date=March 20, 2019|url-status=live|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref name=\"auto18\">{{cite web|url=https://wethepeople2019.org/|title=We The People Membership Summit 2019|website=Wethepeople2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427140155/https://wethepeople2019.org/|archive-date=April 27, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=April 24, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''April 3\u20135:''' [[National Action Network]] convention. The second so-called \"cattle call\" event of the campaign. Twelve candidates show up and speak.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalactionnetwork.net/newnews/2019-national-convention-agenda/|title=\u00bb NAN Convention Schedule 2019|website=nationalactionnetwork.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/presidential-candidates-resonate-black-voters-national-action-network/story?id=62138159|title=Presidential candidates try to resonate with black voters at the National Action Network Convention|date=April 5, 2019|website=ABC News}}</ref>\n*'''April 4''': Representative [[Tim Ryan (Ohio politician)|Tim Ryan]] of Ohio announces his candidacy for the Democratic Party nomination.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/ohio-rep-tim-ryan-throws-his-name-growing-2020-field-n990841|title=Ohio Rep. Tim Ryan throws his name into growing 2020 field|date=April 4, 2019|publisher=[[NBC]]|author=Ali Vitali}}</ref>\n*'''April 8''':\n**Senator [[Mike Gravel]] of Alaska announces his candidacy for the Democratic Party nomination.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MikeGravel/status/1115298261215014912|title=\"I'm Mike Gravel, and I'm running for President.\" Together, we are the #Gravelanche. Get Mike to the debates and get this trending! Welcome to the #Gravelanche.|last=Gravel|first=Mike|date=2019-04-08|website=@MikeGravel|language=en|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref>\n**Representative [[Eric Swalwell]] of California announces his candidacy for the Democratic Party nomination.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tolan|first1=Casey|title=Eric Swalwell jumps into presidential race with long-shot White House bid|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/04/08/eric-swalwell-presidential-announcement-california/|newspaper=The Mercury News|date=April 8, 2019|accessdate=April 8, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''April 14''': Buttigieg officially announces his candidacy for the Democratic Party nomination,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/mayor-presidential-contender-pete-buttigieg-officially-enter-2020/story?id=62345455|title=Pete Buttigieg, little-known mayor turned presidential contender, makes historic bid|last1=Karson|last2=Gomez|first1=Kendall|first2=Justin|date=April 14, 2019|work=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=April 14, 2019}}</ref> having previously formed an exploratory committee earlier in January ''(see above)''.\n*'''April 15''': Weld officially announces his candidacy for the Republican Party nomination,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/04/15/politics/bill-weld-2020-trump/|title=Bill Weld officially announces he is challenging Trump for GOP nomination in 2020|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=April 15, 2019}}</ref> having previously formed an exploratory committee earlier in February ''(see above)''.\n*'''April 22''': Representative [[Seth Moulton]] of Massachusetts announces his candidacy for the Democratic Party nomination.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/rep-seth-moulton-latest-democrat-enter-2020-field-n996881|title=Rep. Seth Moulton is latest Democrat to enter 2020 field|date=April 22, 2019|access-date=April 22, 2019|last=Seitz-Wald|first=Alex|work=[[NBC News]]}}</ref>\n* '''April 24''': Eight Democratic candidates attend the She the People Presidential Forum at [[Texas Southern University]] in [[Houston|Houston, Texas]], discussing issues affecting women of color.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/first-ever-forum-women-color-presidential-contenders-n987181|title=First-ever forum on women of color for presidential contenders|publisher=NBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327020324/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/first-ever-forum-women-color-presidential-contenders-n987181|archive-date=March 27, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto17\">{{cite web|url=https://www.shethepeople.org/savethedate|title=Save The Date - Presidential Forum|website=She the People|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326211924/https://www.shethepeople.org/savethedate|archive-date=March 26, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 26, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''April 25''': Former vice president [[Joe Biden]] announces his candidacy for the Democratic Party nomination. He becomes the 20th [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries#Declared candidates|major Democratic candidate]] to enter the race.<ref name=\"BidenCandidacy\">{{cite web |last1=Burns |first1=Alexander |title=Joe Biden Is Running for President, After Months of Hesitation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/25/us/politics/joe-biden-2020.html |website=The New York Times |date=April 25, 2019 | accessdate=April 25, 2019}}</ref>\n* '''April 27''': Several Democratic candidates attend the National Forum on Wages and Working People at Enclave in [[Las Vegas|Las Vegas, Nevada]], discussing economic issues affecting low-income Americans.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/top-2020-democrats-booked-las-vegas-labor-forum-april-n987686|title=Top 2020 Democrats booked for Las Vegas labor forum in April|publisher=NBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328032459/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/top-2020-democrats-booked-las-vegas-labor-forum-april-n987686|archive-date=March 28, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto24\">{{cite web|url=https://www.workersforum.org/|title=National Forum on Wages and Working People: Creating an Economy that Works for All|publisher=[[Center for American Progress|CAPAF]] and [[SEIU]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424203122/https://www.workersforum.org/|archive-date=April 24, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=April 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== May 2019 ===\n[[File:Beto O'Rourke (48006058187).jpg|thumb|[[Beto O'Rourke]] speaking at the 2019 California State Democratic Convention, held from May&nbsp;31 to June&nbsp;2]]\n\n*'''May 2''': Senator [[Michael Bennet]] of Colorado announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gregorian |first1=Dareh |title=Colorado Sen. Bennet enters presidential race after prostate cancer treatment |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/colorado-sen-bennet-enters-presidential-race-after-prostate-cancer-treatment-n1000971 |website=NBC News |accessdate=May 2, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n*'''May 14''': Governor [[Steve Bullock (American politician)|Steve Bullock]] of Montana announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/14/us/politics/steve-bullock-2020.html|title=Steve Bullock, Montana Governor, Is Running for President|last=Martin|first=Jonathan|date=2019-05-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-05-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*'''May 16''': \n** New York City Mayor [[Bill de Blasio]] announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party.<ref name=\"DeBlasioPreAnnouncement\">{{cite news|title=New York City Mayor Bill de Blasio to announce his 2020 presidential bid |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/york-city-mayor-bill-de-blasio-announce-2020/story?id=63007952|publisher=ABC News|author=Beatrice Peterson, Zohreen Shah and Justin Gomez|date=May 15, 2019|accessdate=May 15, 2019}}</ref>\n** Businessman and perennial candidate [[Rocky De La Fuente]] announces his candidacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Roque_De_La_Fuente_presidential_campaign,_2020|title=Rocky De La Fuente presidential campaign, 2020|publisher=Ballotpedia}}</ref>\n* '''May 28''': Green Party co-founder and perennial candidate [[Howie Hawkins]] announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Green Party.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesunion.com/news/article/Howie-Hawkins-will-seek-Green-nomination-for-13900737.php|title=Howie Hawkins will seek Green nomination for president|date=May 28, 2019|accessdate=October 6, 2019|work=[[Times Union (Albany)|Times Union]]}}</ref>\n* '''May 31''': Castro, Inslee, Harris, and Sanders discuss immigration reform at the Unity and Freedom Forum at the Hilton Pasadena, in [[Pasadena, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2019/05/31/bernie-sanders-blasts-trump-as-racist-over-immigration-in-california/1306282001/|title=Bernie Sanders blasts Trump as 'racist' at forum on immigration|work=USA Today|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190601032804/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2019/05/31/bernie-sanders-blasts-trump-as-racist-over-immigration-in-california/1306282001/|archive-date=June 1, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=June 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto19\">{{cite web|url=https://firmaction.org/presidentialforum|title=Unity & Freedom Presidential Forum|website=FIRM Action|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604001406/https://firmaction.org/presidentialforum|archive-date=June 4, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=June 8, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''May 31-June 2:''' California State Democratic Convention, a major \"cattle call\" event attended by most major candidates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cadem.org/events/2019-california-democratic-party-state-convention-may-31-june-2-2019|title=2019 California Democratic Party State Convention, May 31 - June 2, 2019|website=California Democratic Party}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-2020-democratic-candidates-president-california-party-convention-20190603-story.html|title=14 Democratic presidential candidates give California its Cinderella moment|first=Mark Z.|last=Barabak|first2=Melanie|last2=Mason|website=latimes.com}}</ref> Joe Biden is a no-show at the event, attending a [[Human Rights Campaign]] event in Ohio at the same time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/03/politics/2020-democrats-california-progressives-joe-biden/index.html|title=Joe Biden's rift with progressives on display as he skips California Democratic convention|first=Eric|last=Bradner|website=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://politi.co/2I5MGYk|title=Biden gambles on high-risk primary strategy|first1=Natasha|last1=Korecki|first2=Marc|last2=Caputo|website=POLITICO}}</ref>\n\n=== June 2019 ===\n[[File:Trump Keep America Great 2020 in Orlando.jpg|thumb|[[Donald Trump]] officially kicking-off his re-election campaign in Orlando, Florida on June 18, 2019]]\n\n*'''June 1''': Several Democratic candidates attend the Big Ideas Forum at [[Warfield Theatre]] in [[San Francisco, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/05/09/moveon-democratic-candidate-forum-1313150|title=MoveOn to host Democratic candidate forum in June|date=May 9, 2019|website=Politico|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509143816/https://www.politico.com/story/2019/05/09/moveon-democratic-candidate-forum-1313150|archive-date=May 9, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=May 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''June 5:''' Iowa Democrats' Hall of Fame Dinner: an event featuring 19 candidates. Due to his granddaughter's high school graduation, Biden is absent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2019/06/09/watch_live_19_democratic_presidential_candidates_speak_in_iowa.html|title=19 Democratic Presidential Candidates Speak At Iowa Dinner|first1=Tim|last1=Hains|date=June 9, 2019|website=www.realclearpolitics.com}}</ref>\n*'''June 13:''' The Democratic National Committee announces that 20 candidates will participate in the first official [[2020 Democratic Party presidential debates and forums|Democratic debate]] on June 26\u201327.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/dnc-names-20-candidates-who-will-appear-stage-first-democratic-n1017316|title=DNC names 20 candidates who will appear on stage for first Democratic debate|first=Adam|last=Edelman|work=[[NBC News]]|date=June 13, 2019|accessdate=June 15, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''June 15''': Several Democratic candidates attend the Presidential Candidates Forum at Charleston Music Hall in [[Charleston, South Carolina]], televised on a tape delay on [[BET]].<ref>{{