-sestak-announces-run-for-president-20190623-bmsevkhpizcyril3jbfclqhk7a-story.html|newspaper=The Morning Call|date=June 23, 2019|accessdate=June 23, 2019}}</ref> Sestak cited his daughter's fight with brain cancer as his reason for his delayed June announcement.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Judd|first1=Donald|title=Former Pennsylvania Democratic Rep. Joe Sestak declares run for president in surprise announcement|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/23/politics/joe-sestak-president-campaign/index.html|publisher=CNN|date=June 23, 2019|accessdate=June 23, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''June 26\u201327:''' The Democratic debate series commences with a two-night debate at the [[Adrienne Arsht Center]] in downtown [[Miami]], hosted by NBC and broadcast on its networks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=Ted |title=DNC Announces Plan for 12 Presidential Primary Debates; First Slated for June |url=https://variety.com/2018/politics/news/dnc-2020-presidential-debates-schedule-1203094098/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety.com]] |accessdate=December 20, 2018 |date=December 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/nbc-news-first-democratic-debate-set-miami-june-26-27-n988481|title=NBC News: First Democratic debate set for Miami, June 26\u201327|website=NBC News|author=Allan Smith|date=March 28, 2019|accessdate=March 28, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''June 30''': New Hampshire state representative [[Max Abramson]] announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Libertarian Party.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maxabramson.org/home/june-30th-2019|title=\nREP. MAX ABRAMSON ANNOUNCES PRESIDENTIAL BID--BRING THE TROOPS HOME|date=June 30, 2019|accessdate=October 6, 2019|author=Abramson, Max}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seacoastonline.com/news/20190728/seabrooks-abramson-seeks-libertarian-presidential-nomination|title=Seabrook\u2019s Abramson seeks Libertarian presidential nomination|date=July 28, 2019|accessdate=October 6, 2019|author=Sullivan, Max|work=[[The Portsmouth Herald]]}}</ref>\n\n=== July 2019===\n[[File:Bernie Sanders (48235456926).jpg|thumb|[[Bernie Sanders]] campaigning at the [[Ames, Iowa]] July 4 parade, 2019]]\n\n*'''July 5''': Issues affecting public schools are discussed by Democratic candidates at the Strong Public Schools Presidential Forum at the [[George R. Brown Convention Center]] in [[Houston, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/06/14/teachers-union-rolls-out-plans-for-2020-forum-in-houston-1365388|title=Teachers union rolls out plans for 2020 forum in Houston|last=Gaudiano|first=Nicole|date=June 14, 2019|work=[[Politico]]|accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto21\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nea.org/home/75033.htm|title=NEA Announces #StrongPublicSchools Presidential Forum|publisher=National Education Association|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616041312/http://www.nea.org/home/75033.htm|archive-date=June 16, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=June 15, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''July 8:''' Swalwell becomes the second candidate, after Ojeda on January 25, to drop out of the Democratic nomination race. Swalwell says that he wanted to narrow the crowded Democratic field after he felt that he did not have a path to winning it himself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/08/politics/eric-swalwell-ends-campaign/index.html|title=Eric Swalwell ends presidential bid after failing to gain traction|author1==Rebecca Buck |author2=Dan Merica |author3=Kate Sullivan|website=CNN|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref>\n*'''July 9:''' Hedge fund manager [[Tom Steyer]] of California announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Burns |first1=Alexander |title=Tom Steyer Will Run for President and Plans to Spend $100 Million on His Bid |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/09/us/politics/tom-steyer-president.html |accessdate=July 9, 2019 |issue=July 9, 2019 |publisher=The New York Times}}</ref>\n*'''July 11''': Issues affecting Hispanic and Latino Americans are discussed by Democratic candidates at the League of United Latin American Citizens (LULAC) Presidential Candidates Forum at the [[Wisconsin Center]] in [[Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]].<ref name=\"lulac\">{{cite web |title=LULAC Presidential Town Hall |url=https://lulac.org/convention19/lulac_presidential_town_hall_closed/ |publisher=League of United Latin American Citizens |accessdate=July 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=LULAC Presidential Candidates Forum |url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?462452-1/democratic-presidential-candidates-speak-league-united-latin-american-citizens-forum |publisher=C-SPAN |accessdate=July 15, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''July 11\u201313''': Castro, Gillibrand, Inslee, and Warren make appearances at the [[Netroots Nation]] at the [[Pennsylvania Convention Center]] [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] by the Netroots Foundation.<ref name=\"nrn\">{{cite news |last1=Krieg |first1=Gregory |title=Elizabeth Warren headlines liberal gathering as other top 2020 contenders skip Netroots |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/13/politics/elizabeth-warren-netroots-nation-2019-progressive-convention/index.html |accessdate=July 14, 2019 |issue=July 13, 2019 |publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n*'''July 15\u201320''': Twenty Democratic candidates make appearances at the Iowa Presidential Candidate Forums in [[Des Moines, Iowa|Des Moines]], [[Davenport, Iowa|Davenport]], [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa|Cedar Rapids]], [[Sioux City, Iowa|Sioux City]], and [[Council Bluffs, Iowa|Council Bluffs]].<ref name=aarp>{{cite web|url=https://states.aarp.org/iowa/aarp-and-the-des-moines-register-announce-iowa-presidential-candidate-forums|title=Get Tickets \u2013 AARP and The Des Moines Register Iowa Presidential Candidate Forums|work=[[AARP|AARP Iowa]]|accessdate=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''July 18:''' [[CNN]] announces the lineup for the second Democratic debate to be held July 30\u201331.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/18/us/politics/next-democratic-debate-cnn.html|title=Here are the lineups for the next Democratic debate|date=July 18, 2019|website=The New York Times|author=Matt Stevens|accessdate=July 22, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''July 24''': Ten Democratic candidates appear at the 2020 Presidential Candidates Forum in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]].<ref name=\"naacp\">{{cite web|url=https://naacp.org/candidatesforum/|title=2020 Presidential Candidates Forum|work=[[NAACP]]|accessdate=July 18, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''July 30:''' Democratic governor [[Gavin Newsom]] of California signs a bill into state law requiring presidential candidates to release their tax returns for the past five years in order to qualify for the California primary ballot. It is intended to force President Trump to reveal his taxes, which he has refused to do since his 2016 campaign. Republicans view this as unconstitutional, claiming that a state cannot mandate additional eligibility requirements for the presidency beyond what is stated in [[Article Two of the United States Constitution#Clause 5: Qualifications for office|Article Two]] of the [[United States Constitution|US Constitution]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/30/politics/california-presidential-tax-returns-trump-2020/index.html | title=California governor signs bill requiring presidential candidates to submit tax returns | publisher=CNN | date=July 30, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''July 30\u201331:''' The second Democratic debate commences with a two-night debate at the [[Fox Theatre (Detroit)|Fox Theatre]] in [[Detroit]], airing on CNN.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/02/politics/cnn-2020-democratic-debate-july-detroit/index.html|title=CNN's 2020 Democratic debate set for July 30-31 in Detroit|date=April 2, 2019|website=CNN|author=Devan Cole|accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== August 2019===\n[[File:Andrew Yang (48609991976).jpg|thumb|[[Andrew Yang]] at the Presidential Gun Sense Forum on August 10, 2019]]\n\n* '''August 1:''' Gravel becomes the third candidate to drop out of the Democratic nomination race, citing a failure to qualify for either Democratic debates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/long-shot-candidate-mike-gravels-campaign-closing-shop/story?id=64706997|title=Mike Gravel's 2020 campaign is closing up shop|last=ABC|first=Sruthi Palaniappan and Cheyenne Haslett|website=ABC News|accessdate=August 2, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''August 3''': Nineteen Democratic candidates attend the Public Service Forum at the [[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]].<ref name=\"afscme\">{{cite web|url=https://news3lv.com/politics/presidential-candidates-flock-to-las-vegas-for-public-service-forum-campaign-events|title=2020 Public Service Forum|work=[[KSNV]]|accessdate=July 30, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''August 5\u20136:''' Lawsuits are filled to challenge California's new law that will prevent President Trump from appearing on the state's primary ballot unless he releases his tax returns. The first lawsuit is filled by the conservative activist group [[Judicial Watch]] on behalf of four California voters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/finance/456250-voters-sue-california-over-tax-return-law-targeting-trump|title=Voters sue California over tax return law targeting Trump|publisher=The Hill|date=August 5, 2019}}</ref> Additional lawsuits are filed on August 6 by the Trump campaign, the Republican National Committee, and the [[California Republican Party]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/states/california/story/2019/08/06/new-gop-lawsuits-challenge-newsom-on-trump-tax-bill-1132143|title=New GOP lawsuits challenge Newsom on Trump tax bill|publisher=Politico|date=August 6, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''August 8\u201318:''' The [[Iowa State Fair]] takes place, and is attended by at least twenty of the candidates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iowastatefair.org/entertainment/fair-schedule/|title=Fair Schedule|website=Iowa State Fair}}</ref>\n* '''August 10''': Seventeen Democratic candidates discuss gun issues at the Gun Sense Forum in [[Des Moines, Iowa]].<ref name=\"gunsenseforum\">{{cite web|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/presidential/caucus/2019/08/07/gun-mass-shootings-regulation-iowa-el-paso-dayton-policy-presidential-everytown-2020-trump-democrats/1946231001/|title=17 presidential candidates will attend Saturday's gun forum in Des Moines. Here's what to expect.|work=[[Des Moines Register]]|accessdate=August 7, 2019|author=Robin Opsahl}}</ref>\n*'''August 15''': Hickenlooper becomes the fourth candidate to drop out of the Democratic nomination race. His campaign cites low poll numbers, lack of donors, a large turnover of campaign staff in July, and the likelihood of not qualifying for the third Democratic debate in September.<ref>{{cite news|first=Briana|last=Stewart|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/john-hickenlooper-end-2020-white-house-bid/story?id=64974362|title=John Hickenlooper ends 2020 White House bid|publisher=[[ABC News]]|date=August 15, 2019}}</ref>\n*''' August 19''': In the [[Iowa State Fair Straw Poll]], Biden edged Warren by 10 votes among Democratic primary candidates, while Trump won at least 96 percent of the vote among Republican primary candidates.<ref>{{cite news | first=Jay | last=Greene | url=https://www.kcrg.com/content/news/Biden-wins-Iowa-State-Fair-straw-poll-554351921.html | title=Biden wins Iowa State Fair straw poll | publisher=KCRG-TV | date=August 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/458087-biden-edges-warren-in-iowa-state-fair-straw-poll|title=Biden edges Warren in Iowa state fair straw poll|publisher=The Hill|date=August 20, 2019}}</ref>\n* '''August 19\u201320''': Democratic candidates discuss issues affecting Native Americans at the Frank LaMere Native American Presidential Forum at Orpheum Theater in [[Sioux City, Iowa]].<ref name=\"siouxnativeforum\">{{cite web|url=https://siouxcityjournal.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/sioux-city-s-orpheum-to-host-presidential-candidate-forum-on/article_e2b1b41c-32f1-524d-8c2e-f840859e4057.html|title=Sioux City's Orpheum to host presidential candidate forum on Native American issues in August|work=[[Sioux City Journal]]|accessdate=August 5, 2019|author1=Mason Dockter}}</ref>\n*''' August 21''': Inslee becomes the fifth candidate to drop out of the Democratic nomination race.<ref name=\"InsleeWithdraw\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/jay-inslee-drops-out-2020-presidential-race-n1045066|title=Jay Inslee drops out of the 2020 presidential race|date=August 21, 2019|accessdate=August 21, 2019|author=Dareh Gregorian|publisher=NBC News}}</ref> Unlikely to qualify for the third Democratic debate in September, he decides to instead run for another term as governor of Washington.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/21/us/politics/jay-inslee-2020-campaign.html|title=Jay Inslee, Dropping Out of 2020 Race, Will Run for Governor Again|date=August 22, 2019|accessdate=August 22, 2019|author=Alexander Burns and Matt Steven|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref>\n*''' August 23''': Moulton becomes the sixth candidate to drop out of the Democratic primary. Never able to gather enough fundraising or to register in the polls, he decides to instead run for another term in the House of Representatives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/08/23/politics/seth-moulton-drops-out-2020-race/index.html|title=Seth Moulton to end 2020 presidential election bid|date=August 23, 2019|accessdate=August 23, 2019|author=Dan Merica|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n*'''August 25:''' Former congressman [[Joe Walsh (Illinois politician)|Joe Walsh]] from Illinois announces his candidacy for the Republican Party nomination, becoming Trump's second official primary challenger after Weld.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/exclusive-joe-walsh-announces-republican-primary-challenge-president/story?id=65122073|title='This Week' Exclusive: Joe Walsh announces Republican primary challenge against Trump|date=August 25, 2019|publisher=ABC News}}</ref>\n*'''August 28:'''\n** Gillibrand becomes the seventh candidate to drop out of the Democratic primary, citing her inability to qualify for the third Democratic debate in September.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/08/28/gillibrand-exits-presidential-race-1477644|title=Gillibrand exits presidential race|date=August 28, 2019|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n** Only 10 candidates qualify for the third Democratic debate. Both Gabbard and Steyer criticize its stricter polling criteria that led to their disqualification.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/08/28/september-democratic-debate-one-night-1476645|title=Democratic debate stage to shrink barring last-minute shock|date=August 28, 2019|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n* '''August 31:''' Due to security concerns, the Democratic National Committee orders both the Iowa and Nevada Democratic state parties to scrap their plans for \"virtual caucuses\", which would have allowed those unable to physically attend the [[2020 Iowa Democratic caucuses|Iowa]] or [[2020 Nevada Democratic caucuses|Nevada Democratic caucuses]] to participate online or by teleconference.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/08/30/iowa-dnc-caucus-1479172|title=DNC throws Iowa, Nevada caucuses into confusion|date=August 31, 2019|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n=== September 2019===\n[[File:NH convention 20190907-DSC03495 (48700564848).jpg|thumb|[[Amy Klobuchar]] speaking at the New Hampshire Democratic state convention on September 7, 2019]]\n\n* '''September 4''': [[CNN]] holds and broadcasts a live seven-hour ''Climate Crisis Town Hall'' from [[New York City]] with the 10 candidates who qualified for the third Democratic debate, who appear one-at-a-time for roughly 40 minutes each.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/25/politics/cnn-climate-crisis-town-hall/index.html|title=Climate Change Townhall|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/08/27/politics/cnn-climate-crisis-town-hall-democrats/index.html|title=CNN announces details for climate crisis town hall|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}</ref>\n* '''September 6''': Schultz announces that he will instead not seek an independent presidential bid.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/09/06/politics/howard-schultz-presidential-campaign-2020/index.html|title=Howard Schultz drops plans to run as independent candidate in 2020|work=CNN|date=September 6, 2019|accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''September 7:'''\n** Kansas, Nevada, and South Carolina Republican state committees vote to cancel their respective primary/caucuses. Both of Trump's major challengers, Walsh and Weld, criticize the move.<ref name=\"ap20190907\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7e04964fc89a4312a6b410096f256add|title=Nevada, SC, Kansas GOP drop presidential nomination votes|first=Meg|last=Kinnard|work=Associated Press|date=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n** Nineteen Democratic candidates appear at the New Hampshire Democratic state convention.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/07/us/politics/democrats-new-hampshire.html|title=Elizabeth Warren Stands Out at New Hampshire Democratic Party Convention|first=Katie|last=Glueck|newspaper=The New York Times|date=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''September 8:'''\n** Former South Carolina governor and congressman [[Mark Sanford]] announces his candidacy for the Republican Party nomination, becoming Trump's third official primary challenger.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/08/us/politics/mark-sanford-president.html|title=Mark Sanford Will Challenge Trump in Republican Primary|website=New York Times|date=September 8, 2019}}</ref>\n** Gabbard, Steyer, and Yang attend the Asian American Pacific Islanders Progressive Democratic Presidential Forum at the [[Segerstrom Center for the Arts]] in [[Costa Mesa, California]].<ref name=latsept8>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/socal/daily-pilot/news/story/2019-09-08/three-democratic-presidential-hopefuls-costa-mesa|title=Three Democratic presidential hopefuls state their case at forum in Costa Mesa|last=Zint|first=Bradley|date=September 8, 2019|website=Los Angeles Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''September 9:''' The Arizona Republican Party officially notifies Arizona secretary of state [[Katie Hobbs]] that they will scrap the Arizona Republican primary.<ref name=\"ktar20190909\">{{cite news|url=https://ktar.com/story/2734796/arizona-gop-wont-hold-2020-presidential-preference-election/|title=Arizona GOP won\u2019t hold 2020 presidential preference election|publisher=KTAR|date=September 9, 2019|accessdate=September 12, 2019|author=Kevin Stone}}</ref>\n*'''September 12:''' The third Democratic debate takes place at [[Health and Physical Education Arena|H&PE Arena]] on the campus of [[Texas Southern University]] in [[Houston]], airing on ABC and Univision.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialbuzz.com/dnc-raises-requirements-to-qualify-for-third-presidential-debate/ |title=DNC Raises Requirements to Qualify for Third Presidential Debate |last=Shin |first=Bryan |date=May 30, 2019 |work=FinancialBuzz |access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=TSU Selected as Venue for Democratic Primary Debate |url=http://www.tsu.edu/news/2019/07/tsu-venue-for-dem-primary-debate.html|work=[[Texas Southern University]]|date=July 21, 2019 |accessdate=July 22, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''September 17:''' Six Democratic candidates appear at the Workers' Presidential Summit at the [[Pennsylvania Convention Center]] in [[Philadelphia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phillymag.com/news/2019/09/17/presidential-summit/|title=Biden, Sanders Among 6 Democratic Presidential Candidates in Philly on Tuesday|last=Sasko|first=Claire|date=September 17, 2019|website=Philadelphia Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2019}}</ref>\n* '''September 19\u201320''': A Climate Forum, sponsored by [[MSNBC]], takes place at [[Gaston Hall]] on the campus of [[Georgetown University]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"climateforumdc\">{{Cite web|url=https://thinkprogress.org/democrats-climate-debate-forum-sunrise-movement-dnc-cnn-msnbc-56d099e7748c/|title=In a historic first, two climate forums announced for 2020 Democratic candidates|author=E. A. Crunden|work=[[ThinkProgress]]|date=July 26, 2019|accessdate=August 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/the-energy-202/2019/09/20/the-energy-202-four-big-takeways-from-the-msnbc-climate-change-town-hall/5d83b04b88e0fa0ba8961cad/|title=The Energy 202: Four big takeaways from the MSNBC climate change town hall|newspaper=Washington Post|date=September 20, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''September 20:'''\n** de Blasio becomes the eighth candidate to drop out of the Democratic primary, admitting that he had no chance of winning the nomination.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/20/politics/bill-de-blasio-ends-presidential-campaign/index.html|title=De Blasio drops out of 2020 presidential race|publisher=CNN|date=September 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/09/20/bill-de-blasio-ends-2020-presidential-campaign-1506011|title=Bill de Blasio ends 2020 presidential campaign|publisher=Politico|date=September 20, 2019}}</ref>\n** Ten Democratic candidates appear at the LGBTQ Forum on the campus of [[Coe College]] in [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.advocate.com/politics/2019/8/28/2020-presidential-lgbtq-forum-gets-support-glaad-livestream-date|title=2020 Presidential LGBTQ Forum Gets Support From GLAAD, Live Stream|date=August 28, 2019|website=The Advocate}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/identities/2019/9/21/20876742/lgbtq-presidential-forum-winners-losers|title=2 winners and 3 losers from the LGBTQ presidential forum|date=September 20, 2019|website=Vox}}</ref>\n*'''September 21:'''\n** Buttigieg, Castro, Sanders, and Warren appear at the Iowa People's Presidential Forum at the Iowa Events Center in [[Des Moines, Iowa]].<ref name=\"auto29\">{{Cite web|url=https://peoplesaction.org/peoples-presidential-forums/|title=People\u2019s Presidential Forums|date=January 28, 2019|website=People's Action|language=en-US|access-date=July 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/presidential/caucus/2019/09/21/iowa-cci-peoples-presidential-forum-bernie-sanders-pete-buttigieg-democrat-socialist-progressive-dsm/2405666001/|title=A warm reception for liberal presidential candidates, lion's den for moderates at CCI forum in Iowa|date=September 21, 2019|newspaper=Des Moines Register}}</ref>\n** The Alaska Republican Party officially scraps its state's Republican primary, stating it \"would serve no useful purpose\" because Trump is the incumbent president.<ref name=\"abc20190921\">{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/alaska-gop-scraps-2020-presidential-primary-helping-trump-65773870|title=Alaska GOP scraps 2020 presidential primary, helping Trump|work=Associated Press|publisher=ABC News|date=September 21, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''September 22:''' Six Democratic candidates appear at the Youth Forum at [[Theodore Roosevelt High School (Des Moines)|Roosevelt High School]] in [[Des Moines, Iowa]].<ref name=\"youthforum1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dmschools.org/news_release/dmps-register-sponsor-youth-voice-forum-presidential-candidates/|title=DMPS, Register Host Youth Forum for Presidential Candidates|date=September 11, 2019|website=Des Moines Public Schools|access-date=September 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* '''September 24:''' \n**[[Nancy Pelosi]], the [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|speaker of the House of Representatives]], announces the start of a formal [[Impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump|impeachment inquiry against Trump]].<ref name=\"WashPo 2019-09-24\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/pelosi-top-democrats-privately-discuss-creation-of-select-committee-for-impeachment/2019/09/24/af6f735a-dedf-11e9-b199-f638bf2c340f_story.html|title=Pelosi announces impeachment inquiry, says Trump\u2019s courting of foreign political help is a \u2018betrayal of national security\u2019|last=Bade|first=Rachael|date=September 24, 2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=September 24, 2019|last2=DeBonis|first2=Mike}}</ref>\n** ''[[Business Insider]]'' hosts a non-RNC-sanctioned debate between Walsh and Weld, streamed live on both their website and their [[Facebook Watch]] show ''Business Insider Today''. Sanford and Trump decline to participate.<ref name=\"Fox20190912\">{{cite news|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/long-shot-gop-presidential-primary-challengers-to-face-off-in-debate-this-month|author=Paul Steinhauser|title=Long-shot GOP primary challengers to have their own debate this month \u2013 minus Trump|website=Fox News|accessdate=September 12, 2019|date=September 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Insider20190917\">{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/how-to-watch-republican-presidential-debate-2019-9|title=How to watch the first-ever 2020 Republican presidential debate|first=Grace|last=Panetta|work=[[Business Insider]]|date=September 17, 2019|accessdate=September 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== October 2019===\n[[File:Mayor Pete at Roosevelt High School (48890696318).jpg|thumb|[[Pete Buttigieg]] at a town hall at [[Theodore Roosevelt High School (Des Moines)|Roosevelt High School]] in Des Moines, Iowa on October 12, 2019]]\n\n* '''October 1:''' Twelve candidates qualify for the fourth Democratic debate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/whos-in-and-whos-out-of-the-october-debate/|title=Who Has \u2014 And Hasn\u2019t \u2014 Qualified For The October Democratic Debate|website=[[FiveThirtyEight]]|date=October 1, 2019|accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n* '''October 2:'''\n** Sanders undergoes an unexpected heart surgery to treat a blocked artery, postponing his campaign events for at least a few days.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/10/02/4bf1660a-e522-11e9-a331-2df12d56a80b_story.html|title=Bernie Sanders undergoes unexpected heart procedure, postpones campaign events for at least a few days|newspaper=Washington Post|date=October 2, 2019|accessdate=October 2, 2019}}</ref>\n** Nine Democratic candidates appear at the Gun Safety Forum in [[Las Vegas|Las Vegas, Nevada]]<ref name=\"firearmforum\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/gun-safety-groups-to-host-presidential-forum|title=Gun violence forum hosted in Las Vegas, day after second anniversary of Las Vegas massacre.|date=August 1, 2019|work=PBS}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/2020-candidates-convene-gun-safety-forum-heels-las/story?id=65980074|title=2020 candidates convene on gun safety forum on the heels of Las Vegas shooting anniversary|publisher=ABC News|date=October 2, 2019|accessdate=October 2, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''October 10''': Nine Democratic candidates appear at the LGBTQ Forum in [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newsroom.ucla.edu/releases/ucla-human-rights-campaign-2020-presidential-candidates-forum|title=UCLA and Human Rights Campaign to host 2020 presidential candidates forum|website=UCLA}}</ref><ref name=\"auto28\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/politics/article/California-to-host-Democratic-presidential-debate-13698482.php|title=Democratic presidential forum on LGBTQ issues will be held in California|date=March 19, 2019|work=San Francisco Chronicle|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190319232511/https://www.sfchronicle.com/politics/article/California-to-host-Democratic-presidential-debate-13698482.php|archive-date=March 19, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/465347-democratic-2020-hopefuls-push-lgbtq-agenda-at-town-hall|title=Democratic 2020 hopefuls tout LGBTQ plans at town hall|publisher=The Hill|date=October 10, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''October 15:''' The fourth Democratic debate takes place at [[Otterbein University]] in [[Westerville, Ohio]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/9/12/20859539/democratic-debate-october-2019|title=Here\u2019s everything you need to know about the October debate|first=Tara|last=Golsha|date=September 13, 2019|website=Vox}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/27/politics/democratic-debate-october-one-night/index.html|title=October Democratic debate to take place on one night|author=Kyle Blaine|website=CNN|access-date=September 27, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''October 24:''' Ryan becomes the ninth candidate to drop out of the Democratic primary, deciding to instead run for another term as House representative of Ohio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/24/politics/tim-ryan-ends-campaign/index.html|title=Tim Ryan ends presidential campaign|author=Dan Merica|date=October 24, 2019|website=CNN|access-date=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''October 25\u201327:''' At [[Benedict College]] in [[Columbia, South Carolina]], the 20/20 Bipartisan Justice Center gives Trump an award for criminal justice reform. This causes Harris and several other Democratic candidates to threaten to boycott the Second Step Presidential Justice Forum, also being held at Benedict. Harris and the others then agree to rejoin the event after the 20/20 Bipartisan Justice Center removes its sponsorship of the forum.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/10/26/trump-kamala-harris-sc-criminal-justice-forum-058333|title=Blowback from Trump appearance throws HBCU forum into chaos|date=October 26, 2019|newspaper=Politico|access-date=October 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/26/politics/kamala-harris-trump-criminal-justice/index.html|title=Bipartisan group removed from justice forum after protest from Harris and college students|date=October 26, 2019|newspaper=CNN|access-date=October 26, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''October 26:'''\n** Sanford, Walsh, and Weld appear at [[Politicon#Politicon 2019|Politicon 2019]] in [[Nashville, Tennessee]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/politics/2019/10/26/joe-walsh-mark-sanford-bill-weld-republican-candidates-politicon-nashville/4078052002/|title='Never Trump' GOP presidential candidate Joe Walsh says Republicans should consider a Democratic running mate|first=Natalie|last=Allison|date=October 26, 2019|newspaper=The Tennessean|access-date=October 26, 2019}}</ref>\n** Several Democratic candidates appear at the People's Presidential Forum Nevada in [[Las Vegas|Las Vegas, Nevada]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ktnv.com/news/democratic-candidates-make-their-cases-at-presidential-forum-in-east-las-vegas|title=Democratic candidates make their cases at presidential forum in east Las Vegas|first=Jeremy|last=Chen|date=October 26, 2019|newspaper=KTNV|access-date=October 26, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''October 28:''' ''[[Forbes]]'' sponsors a non-RNC-sanctioned debate between Sanford, Walsh, and Weld at the [[Detroit Masonic Temple|Masonic Temple]] in [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbespr/2019/10/25/forbes-under-30-summit-in-detroit-to-feature-republican-presidential-candidate-debate/#7e4635c639bc|title=Forbes Under 30 Summit in Detroit to Feature Republican Presidential Candidate Debate|date=October 26, 2019|website=Forbes|accessdate=October 29, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''October 31:'''\n** The House of Representatives votes to establish procedures for public hearings in the Trump impeachment inquiry, with two Democrats and all Republicans voting against the measure.<ref name=\"cnn20191031\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/31/politics/house-impeachment-inquiry-resolution-floor-vote/index.html|title=House votes to formalize impeachment inquiry procedures|publisher=CNN|date=October 31, 2019|accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/live-news/trump-impeachment-house-resolution-vote-democrats-voted-no-trump-impeachment-rules/ |title=House approves impeachment rules, ushering in new phase of inquiry|last1=Segers |first1=Grace |last2=Watson |first2=Kathryn |last3=Becket |first3=Stefan |date=October 31, 2019 |website=CBS News}}</ref>\n** The Minnesota Republican Party submits its \"determination of candidates\" for its primary ballot to the Minnesota secretary of state, listing only Trump. Sanford and Walsh criticize the move for their exclusion from the Minnesota ballot.<ref name=\"StarTribune20191031\">{{cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/minnesota-republican-party-leaves-trump-challengers-off-presidential-primary-ballot/564160782/|title=Minnesota Republican Party leaves Trump challengers off presidential primary ballot|first=Patrick|last=Condon|newspaper=Star Tribune|date=October 31, 2019}}</ref> Minnesota Republican state party chairwoman Jennifer Carnahan claims that Trump was the only campaign to contact the state party for filing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/468307-trump-primary-challengers-to-be-excluded-from-minnesota-ballot|title=Trump primary challengers to be excluded from Minnesota ballot|date=October 31, 2019|website=The Hill|first=Rachel|last=Frazin}}</ref>\n\n=== November 2019 ===\n[[File:Michael Bloomberg (48604023932).jpg|thumb|[[Michael Bloomberg]] officially launched his campaign on November 24, 2019]]\n\n*'''November 1:'''\n** O'Rourke becomes the tenth candidate to drop out of the Democratic primary, saying that he could not raise enough money to stay competitive in the race.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/01/politics/beto-orourke-drops-out/index.html|title=Beto O'Rourke ends 2020 presidential bid|first=Eric|last=Bradner|publisher=CNN|date=November 