ory-inline|COVID-19 pandemic in Poland}}\n* [https://www.gov.pl/web/zdrowie Ministerstwo Zdrowia - Portal Gov.pl] ([[Ministry of Health (Poland)|Ministry of Health]])\n* [https://gis.gov.pl/kategoria/aktualnosci Aktualno\u015bci] ({{ill|G\u0142\u00f3wny Inspektorat Sanitarny|pl}} (GIS), national health agency)\n* [https://tvn24.pl/polska/koronawirus-w-polsce-kwarantanna-izolacja-nadzor-epidemiologiczny-czym-sie-roznia-4298999 informal and formal definitions of \"isolation\", \"quarantine\" and \"monitoring\"] (in Polish)\n* [https://www.gov.pl/web/koronawirus/wykaz-zarazen-koronawirusem-sars-cov-2 Polish government list of SARS-CoV-2 infections]\n* {{cite news|title = Koronawirus - wyleczeni |url = https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1IkXPT1r1R81tm4nLS7J4u-2rAIgi4QzPvVubJc-Jk2c/edit#gid=0|date = 30 March 2020|website= Google Docs |archiveurl= https://archive.today/Irjtc|url-status=live |archivedate = 30 March 2020}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{medical resources| ICD10 = {{ICD10|U07.1}}, {{ICD10|U07.2}}}}\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Poland]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Poland]]\n[[Category:2020 in Poland]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Poland]]\n", "name_user": "Natanieluz", "label": "safe", "comment": "corrected deaths on 2 April", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Poland"}
{"title_page": "Jeanne Dielman, 23 quai du Commerce, 1080 Bruxelles", "text_new": "{{short description|1975 film by Chantal Akerman}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| image          = JeanneDielman.png\n| name           = Jeanne Dielman, 23, Quai du Commerce, 1080 Bruxelles\n| caption        = French poster\n| director       = [[Chantal Akerman]]\n| producer       = Corinne J\u00e9nart<br>Evelyne Paul\n| writer         = Chantal Akerman\n| starring       = [[Delphine Seyrig]]<br>Jan Decorte<br>[[Jacques Doniol-Valcroze]]\n| cinematography = [[Babette Mangolte]]\n| editing        = Patricia Canino\n| distributor    = [[The Criterion Collection]] (USA DVD)<br>[[Janus Films]] (USA)\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|1975|5|14}}\n| runtime        = 201 minutes\n| budget         = $120,000\n| country        = Belgium<br>France\n| language       = French\n}}\n'''''Jeanne Dielman, 23, Quai du Commerce, 1080 Bruxelles''''', more commonly known simply as '''''Jeanne Dielman''''', ({{IPA-fr|\u0292an dilm\u0251\u0303 v\u025b\u0303 t\u0281w\u0251 ke dy k\u0254me\u0281s mil kat\u0281\u0259v\u025b\u0303 b\u0281ys\u025bl}}, \"Jeanne Dielman, 23 Commerce Quay, 1080 [[Brussels]]\") is a 1975 [[arthouse]] film by Belgian filmmaker [[Chantal Akerman]].\n\nUpon its release, critic {{Ill|Louis Marcorelles|fr}} called it the \"first masterpiece of the feminine in the history of the cinema\".<ref name=Spaas/> It has become a [[cult classic]] and was the 19th-greatest film of the 20th century in a critics poll conducted by ''[[The Village Voice]]''.<ref name=Mathijs /><ref name=\"vv100\" />\n\n==Plot==\n''Jeanne Dielman'' examines a single mother's regimented schedule of cooking, cleaning and mothering over three days. The mother, Jeanne Dielman (whose name is only derived from the title and from a letter she reads to her son), [[prostitution|has sex with male clients]] in her house daily for her and her son's subsistence. Like her other activities, Jeanne's sex work is part of the routine she performs every day by rote and is uneventful. But on the second and third day, Jeanne's routine begins to unravel subtly, as she overcooks the potatoes that she's preparing for dinner, and drops a newly washed spoon. These alterations to Jeanne's existence prepare for the climax on the third day, during which she murders a client.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Delphine Seyrig]] as Jeanne Dielman\n* [[Jan Decorte]] as Sylvain Dielman\n* [[Henri Storck]] as the first client\n* [[Jacques Doniol-Valcroze]] as the second client\n* Yves Bical as the third client\n\n==Production==\nAfter establishing herself as a major film director with ''[[Je, tu, il, elle]]'' (1974), Akerman said that she \"felt ready to make a feature with more money\" and applied for a grant from the Belgian government for financial support, submitting a script that Jane Clarke described as portraying \"a rigorous regimen [constructed] around food&nbsp;... and routine bought sex in the afternoon\". This script would only be the rough basis for ''Jeanne Dielman, 23 quai du Commerce, 1080 Bruxelles'' because after Akerman received the government grant of $120,000 and began production, she threw the script out and began a new film instead.<ref name=Wakeman>Wakeman, John. World Film Directors, Volume 2. The H. W. Wilson Company. 1988. pp. 4, 5.</ref> Akerman also explained that she was able to make a female-centric film because \"at that point everybody was talking about women\" and that it was \"the right time\".<ref name=Wakeman />\n\nShooting ''Jeanne Dielman, 23 quai du Commerce, 1080 Bruxelles'' took five weeks and Akerman called it \"a love film for my mother. It gives recognition to that kind of woman\".<ref name=Wakeman /> Akerman used an all female crew for the film, which she later said \"didn't work that well - not because they were women but because I didn't choose them. It was enough just to be a woman to work on my film&nbsp;... so the shooting was awful\". Akerman further stated that \"a hierarchy of images\" that places a car accident or a kiss \"higher in the hierarchy than washing up&nbsp;... And it's not by accident, but relates to the place of woman in the social hierarchy&nbsp;... Woman's work comes out of oppression and whatever comes out of oppression is more interesting. You have to be definite. You have to ''be''\".<ref name=Wakeman />\n\nThe film depicts the life of Jeanne Dielman in real time, which Akerman said \"was the only way to shoot the film -  to avoid cutting the action in a hundred places, to look carefully and to be respectful. The framing was meant to respect her space, her, and her gestures within it\".<ref name=Wakeman /> The long static shots ensure that the viewer \"always knows where I am.\"<ref name=margulies>{{cite web|last=Margulies|first=Ivone|title=A Matter of Time: Jeanne Dielman, 23, quai du Commerce, 1080 Bruxelles|url=http://www.criterion.com/current/posts/1215-a-matter-of-time-jeanne-dielman-23-quai-du-commerce-1080-bruxelles|work=Film Essays|publisher=The Criterion Collection|accessdate=15 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''Jeanne Dielman, 23 quai du Commerce, 1080 Bruxelles'' premiered at the [[Directors Fortnight]] at the [[1975 Cannes Film Festival]] and was financially successful in Europe. Writer [[Peter Handke]] and filmmaker [[Alain Tanner]] have cited it as influential on their work. It was not released in the United States until 1983.<ref name=Wakeman />\n\nFilm critic John Coleman said that \"the film's time span covers Tuesday (stew and potatoes), Wednesday (wiener schnitzel) and heady Thursday (meat loaf and Jeanne has an orgasm and kills her client with a pair of scissors). This orgasm bit is bound to strike the serious-minded as an unfortunate bow of crass commercialism\".<ref name=Wakeman /> [[Jonathan Rosenbaum]] defended the film and said that it \"needs its running time, for its subject is an epic one, and the overall sweep&nbsp;... trains one to recognize and respond to fluctuations and nuances. If a radical cinema is something that goes to the roots of experience, this is at the very least a film that shows where and how some of these roots are buried\".<ref name=Wakeman /> Critic Gary Indiana said that \"Akerman's brilliance is her ability to keep the viewer fascinated by everything normally left out of movies\".<ref name=Wakeman />\n\nIvone Marguilies observed that the film was \"fully in tune\" with the European women's movement of the time, and that feminist critics welcomed its \"rigorous alignment of sexual/gender politics with a formal economy\u2014showing cooking and hiding sex\u2014... as an impressive alternative to well-intentioned but conventional political documentaries and features.\"<ref name=margulies/> [[B. Ruby Rich]] said that \"never before was the materiality of woman's time in the home rendered so viscerally&nbsp;... She invents a new language capable of transmitting truths previously unspoken\".<ref name=Wakeman /> [[Marsha Kidder]] called it \"the best feature that I have ever seen made by a woman\".<ref name=Wakeman /> Akerman was reluctant to be seen as a feminist filmmaker, stating that \"I don't think woman's cinema exists\".<ref name=Wakeman />\n\nFilm director [[Gus Van Sant]] named  ''Jeanne Dielman, 23 quai du Commerce, 1080 Bruxelles'' (1975) an inspiration for his own similar films ''[[Gerry (2002 film)|Gerry]]'' (2002) and ''[[Elephant (2003 film)|Elephant]]'' (2003).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elle.fr/Loisirs/Cinema/News/Chantal-Akerman-retour-sur-la-carriere-d-une-cineaste-discrete-3002285|title=Chantal Akerman : retour sur la carri\u00e8re d\u2019une cin\u00e9aste influente|author=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Demay|work=elle.fr|accessdate=14 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Criterion Collection]] includes the film in its Themes section, \"Food on Film.\"<ref>[https://www.criterion.com/explore/101-food-on-film Themes; Food on Film]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist |refs=\n<ref name=Spaas >{{cite book |title=Francophone Film: A Struggle for Identity |last=Spaas |first=Lieve |date=2000 |publisher=Manchester University Press |page=[https://archive.org/details/francophonefilms0000spaa/page/27 27] |isbn=9780719058615 |quote=In ''Le Monde'' Louis Marcorelles referred to the film as 'Undoubtedly the first masterpiece of the feminine in the history of cinema' (Marcorelles ''Le Monde'' 22 January 1976, trans.). |url=https://archive.org/details/francophonefilms0000spaa/page/27 }}</ref>\n<ref name=Mathijs>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uPtuaV7IAt0C&pg=PT140 |title=Cult Cinema: an Introduction |first1=Ernest |last1=Mathijs |first2=Jamie |last2=Sexton |date=2012 |publisher=John Wiley |isbn=978-1-4443-9643-0}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"vv100\">{{cite web |title=100 Best Films of the 20th Century: Village Voice Critics' Poll |url=http://www.filmsite.org/villvoice.html |authorlink=J. Hoberman |last=Hoberman |first=J. |year=2001 |edition=reprint |origyear=4 January 2000 |work=[[The Village Voice]] |publisher=Reprinted by [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331174817/http://www.filmsite.org/villvoice.html |archivedate=31 March 2014 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0073198}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|jeanne_dielman_23_quai_du_commerce_1080_bruxelles}}\n* {{Amg movie|145302}}\n\n{{Chantal Akerman}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1975 films]]\n[[Category:1970s avant-garde and experimental films]]\n[[Category:1970s drama films]]\n[[Category:Belgian avant-garde and experimental films]]\n[[Category:Belgian drama films]]\n[[Category:Belgian films]]\n[[Category:Cooking films]]\n[[Category:1970s feminist films]]\n[[Category:Films about families]]\n[[Category:Films about prostitution in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Films about widowhood]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Chantal Akerman]]\n[[Category:Films set in Brussels]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Brussels]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:Murder in films]]\n[[Category:French political films]]\n[[Category:1970s political films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1975 film by Chantal Akerman}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| image          = JeanneDielman.png\n| name           = Jeanne Dielman, 23, Quai du Commerce, 1080 Bruxelles\n| caption        = French poster\n| director       = [[Chantal Akerman]]\n| producer       = Corinne J\u00e9nart<br>Evelyne Paul\n| writer         = Chantal Akerman\n| starring       = [[Delphine Seyrig]]<br>Jan Decorte<br>[[Jacques Doniol-Valcroze]]\n| cinematography = [[Babette Mangolte]]\n| editing        = Patricia Canino\n| distributor    = [[The Criterion Collection]] (USA DVD)<br>[[Janus Films]] (USA)\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|1975|5|14}}\n| runtime        = 201 minutes\n| budget         = $120,000\n| country        = Belgium<br>France\n| language       = French\n}}\n'''''Jeanne Dielman, 23, Quai du Commerce, 1080 Bruxelles''''', more commonly known simply as '''''Jeanne Dielman''''', ({{IPA-fr|\u0292an dilm\u0251\u0303 v\u025b\u0303 t\u0281w\u0251 ke dy k\u0254me\u0281s mil kat\u0281\u0259v\u025b\u0303 b\u0281ys\u025bl}}, \"Jeanne Dielman, 23 Commerce Quay, 1080 [[Brussels]]\") is a 1975 [[arthouse]] film by Belgian filmmaker [[Chantal Akerman]].\n\nUpon its release, critic {{Ill|Louis Marcorelles|fr}} called it the \"first masterpiece of the feminine in the history of the cinema\".<ref name=Spaas/> It has become a [[cult classic]] and was the 19th-greatest film of the 20th century in a critics poll conducted by ''[[The Village Voice]]''.<ref name=Mathijs /><ref name=\"vv100\" />\n\n==Plot==\n''Jeanne Dielman'' examines a single mother's regimented schedule of cooking, cleaning and mothering over three days. The mother, Jeanne Dielman (whose name is only derived from the title and from a letter she reads to her son), [[prostitution|has sex with male clients]] in her house daily for her and her son's subsistence. Like her other activities, Jeanne's sex work is part of the routine she performs every day by rote and is uneventful. But on the second and third day, Jeanne's routine begins to unravel subtly, as she overcooks the potatoes that she's preparing for dinner, and drops a newly washed spoon. These alterations to Jeanne's existence prepare for the climax on the third day, during which she murders a client.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Delphine Seyrig]] as Jeanne Dielman\n* [[Jan Decorte]] as Sylvain Dielman\n* [[Henri Storck]] as the first client\n* [[Jacques Doniol-Valcroze]] as the second client\n* Yves Bical as the third client\n\n==Production==\nAfter establishing herself as a major film director with ''[[Je, tu, il, elle]]'' (1974), Akerman said that she \"felt ready to make a feature with more money\" and applied for a grant from the Belgian government for financial support, submitting a script that Jane Clarke described as portraying \"a rigorous regimen [constructed] around food&nbsp;... and routine bought sex in the afternoon\". This script would only be the rough basis for ''Jeanne Dielman, 23 quai du Commerce, 1080 Bruxelles'' because after Akerman received the government grant of $120,000 and began production, she threw the script out and began a new film instead.<ref name=Wakeman>Wakeman, John. World Film Directors, Volume 2. The H. W. Wilson Company. 1988. pp. 4, 5.</ref> Akerman also explained that she was able to make a female-centric film because \"at that point everybody was talking about women\" and that it was \"the right time\".<ref name=Wakeman />\n\nShooting ''Jeanne Dielman, 23 quai du Commerce, 1080 Bruxelles'' took five weeks and Akerman called it \"a love film for my mother. It gives recognition to that kind of woman\".<ref name=Wakeman /> Akerman used an all female crew for the film, which she later said \"didn't work that well - not because they were women but because I didn't choose them. It was enough just to be a woman to work on my film&nbsp;... so the shooting was awful\". Akerman further stated that \"a hierarchy of images\" that places a car accident or a kiss \"higher in the hierarchy than washing up&nbsp;... And it's not by accident, but relates to the place of woman in the social hierarchy&nbsp;... Woman's work comes out of oppression and whatever comes out of oppression is more interesting. You have to be definite. You have to ''be''\".<ref name=Wakeman />\n\nThe film depicts the life of Jeanne Dielman in real time, which Akerman said \"was the only way to shoot the film -  to avoid cutting the action in a hundred places, to look carefully and to be respectful. The framing was meant to respect her space, her, and her gestures within it\".<ref name=Wakeman /> The long static shots ensure that the viewer \"always knows where I am.\"<ref name=margulies>{{cite web|last=Margulies|first=Ivone|title=A Matter of Time: Jeanne Dielman, 23, quai du Commerce, 1080 Bruxelles|url=http://www.criterion.com/current/posts/1215-a-matter-of-time-jeanne-dielman-23-quai-du-commerce-1080-bruxelles|work=Film Essays|publisher=The Criterion Collection|accessdate=15 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''Jeanne Dielman, 23 quai du Commerce, 1080 Bruxelles'' premiered at the [[Directors Fortnight]] at the [[1975 Cannes Film Festival]] and was financially successful in Europe. Writer [[Peter Handke]] and filmmaker [[Alain Tanner]] have cited it as influential on their work. It was not released in the United States until 1983.<ref name=Wakeman />\n\nFilm critic John Coleman said that \"the film's time span covers Tuesday (stew and potatoes), Wednesday (wiener schnitzel) and heady Thursday (meat loaf and Jeanne has an orgasm and kills her client with a pair of scissors). This orgasm bit is bound to strike the serious-minded as an unfortunate bow of crass commercialism\".<ref name=Wakeman /> [[Jonathan Rosenbaum]] defended the film and said that it \"needs its running time, for its subject is an epic one, and the overall sweep&nbsp;... trains one to recognize and respond to fluctuations and nuances. If a radical cinema is something that goes to the roots of experience, this is at the very least a film that shows where and how some of these roots are buried\".<ref name=Wakeman /> Critic Gary Indiana said that \"Akerman's brilliance is her ability to keep the viewer fascinated by everything normally left out of movies\".<ref name=Wakeman />\n\nIvone Marguilies observed that the film was \"fully in tune\" with the European women\u2019s movement of the time, and that feminist critics welcomed its \"rigorous alignment of sexual/gender politics with a formal economy\u2014showing cooking and hiding sex\u2014... as an impressive alternative to well-intentioned but conventional political documentaries and features.\"<ref name=margulies/> [[B. Ruby Rich]] said that \"never before was the materiality of woman's time in the home rendered so viscerally&nbsp;... She invents a new language capable of transmitting truths previously unspoken\".<ref name=Wakeman /> [[Marsha Kidder]] called it \"the best feature that I have ever seen made by a woman\".<ref name=Wakeman /> Akerman was reluctant to be seen as a feminist filmmaker, stating that \"I don't think woman's cinema exists\".<ref name=Wakeman />\n\nFilm director [[Gus Van Sant]] named  ''Jeanne Dielman, 23 quai du Commerce, 1080 Bruxelles'' (1975) an inspiration for his own similar films ''[[Gerry (2002 film)|Gerry]]'' (2002) and ''[[Elephant (2003 film)|Elephant]]'' (2003).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elle.fr/Loisirs/Cinema/News/Chantal-Akerman-retour-sur-la-carriere-d-une-cineaste-discrete-3002285|title=Chantal Akerman : retour sur la carri\u00e8re d\u2019une cin\u00e9aste influente|author=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Demay|work=elle.fr|accessdate=14 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Criterion Collection]] includes the film in its Themes section, \"Food on Film.\"<ref>[https://www.criterion.com/explore/101-food-on-film Themes; Food on Film]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist |refs=\n<ref name=Spaas >{{cite book |title=Francophone Film: A Struggle for Identity |last=Spaas |first=Lieve |date=2000 |publisher=Manchester University Press |page=[https://archive.org/details/francophonefilms0000spaa/page/27 27] |isbn=9780719058615 |quote=In ''Le Monde'' Louis Marcorelles referred to the film as 'Undoubtedly the first masterpiece of the feminine in the history of cinema' (Marcorelles ''Le Monde'' 22 January 1976, trans.). |url=https://archive.org/details/francophonefilms0000spaa/page/27 }}</ref>\n<ref name=Mathijs>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uPtuaV7IAt0C&pg=PT140 |title=Cult Cinema: an Introduction |first1=Ernest |last1=Mathijs |first2=Jamie |last2=Sexton |date=2012 |publisher=John Wiley |isbn=978-1-4443-9643-0}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"vv100\">{{cite web |title=100 Best Films of the 20th Century: Village Voice Critics' Poll |url=http://www.filmsite.org/villvoice.html |authorlink=J. Hoberman |last=Hoberman |first=J. |year=2001 |edition=reprint |origyear=4 January 2000 |work=[[The Village Voice]] |publisher=Reprinted by [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331174817/http://www.filmsite.org/villvoice.html |archivedate=31 March 2014 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0073198}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|jeanne_dielman_23_quai_du_commerce_1080_bruxelles}}\n* {{Amg movie|145302}}\n\n{{Chantal Akerman}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1975 films]]\n[[Category:1970s avant-garde and experimental films]]\n[[Category:1970s drama films]]\n[[Category:Belgian avant-garde and experimental films]]\n[[Category:Belgian drama films]]\n[[Category:Belgian films]]\n[[Category:Cooking films]]\n[[Category:1970s feminist films]]\n[[Category:Films about families]]\n[[Category:Films about prostitution in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Films about widowhood]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Chantal Akerman]]\n[[Category:Films set in Brussels]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Brussels]]\n[[Category:French-language films]