iving people]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Prostitution in Belarus]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{short description|Russia escort}}\n'''Anastasia Vashukevich''' ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0438\u044f \u0412\u0430\u0448\u0443\u043a\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447}}), also known as '''Nastya Rybka''' ({{lang-ru|\u041d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044f \u0420\u044b\u0431\u043a\u0430}}) (b. 27 February 1990 [[Babruysk]], [[Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic|Byelorussian SSR]]), is a [[Belarus]]ian [[Escort agency|escort]], model, blogger and author who, while fearing death in a Thai jail,<ref name=\"cnn.com\">{{cite news |title=Belarusian 'sex coach' says she was warned to keep quiet about oligarch Oleg Deripaska |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/29/europe/russia-anastasia-vashukevich-us-election-intl/index.html|work=[[CNN]]|last1=Chance|first1=Matthew|last2=Tarasova|first2=Darya|last3=Hodge|first3=Nathan|date=29 January 2019|access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref> claimed to have evidence linking Russian billionaire [[Oleg Deripaska]] and Deputy Prime Minister [[Sergei Eduardovich Prikhodko|Sergei Prikhodko]] to [[Russian interference in the 2016 U.S. presidential election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lawandcrime.com/high-profile/model-who-claimed-to-have-dirt-on-paul-manafort-linked-russian-billionaire-just-got-out-of-jail/|title=Model Who Claimed to Have Dirt on Paul Manafort-Linked Russian Billionaire Just Got Out of Jail|last=Kalmbacher|first=Colin|date=22 January 2019|website=lawandcrime.com|access-date=22 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"torontosun.com\">{{cite news|url=https://torontosun.com/news/world/a-sex-guru-party-girls-oligarchs-putin-and-trump|title=A sex guru, party girls, oligarchs, Putin and Trump|work=[[Toronto Sun]]|last=Hunter|first=Brad|date=27 January 2019|access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==US election related photographs, video, and audio recordings==\nDuring 2016 to 2017, Vashukevich met with [[Oleg Deripaska]] at least three times: during August 2016{{efn|On 5 August 2016, two of Deripaska's private jets flew to [[Molde Airport, \u00c5r\u00f8|Molde Airport]] a remote airport {{convert|5|km|sp=us}} east of [[Molde]] in Norway: M-ALAY from Moscow and M-UGIC from Montenegro.<ref name=FBK08022018>{{cite news |url=https://fbk.info/english/english/post/403/ |title=Oligarch, yacht, US elections rigging and escort ladies |work=[[Anti-Corruption Foundation|\u0424\u043e\u043d\u0434 \u0431\u043e\u0440\u044c\u0431\u044b \u0441 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0440\u0443\u043f\u0446\u0438\u0435\u0439]] (\u0424\u0411\u041a) |last=Navalny |first=Alexei |author-link=Alexei Navalny |date=8 February 2018 |access-date=5 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>}} on Deripaska's yacht ''Elden''{{efn|''Elden'' ({{lang-ru|\u042d\u041b\u0414\u0415\u041d}}), the smaller of Deripaska's two yachts, is a 29-meter super luxury yacht. His larger yacht is the 2,000 ton ''Queen K'' which is usually seen in warmer climates.<ref name=Sutton05112018>{{cite web |url=http://www.hisutton.com/Yacht_Elden.html |title=Yacht tracking: Russian yacht Elden |work=hisutton.com |last=Sutton |first=H. I. |date=5 November 2018 |access-date=5 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> According to Alexei Navalny, the actual owner of Elden is Yevgeny Agarkov.<ref name=RFE22012019>{{cite news |url=https://www.rferl.org/a/escort-sex-trainer-known-as-nastya-rybka-released-by-police-remains-suspect-lawyer-says/29724568.html |title='Sex Trainer,' Escort 'Nastya Rybka' Released But Remains Suspect, Lawyer Says  |work=[[Radio Free Europe]] |date=22 January 2019 |access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=NavalnyRecordings21012019>{{cite news |url=https://navalny.com/p/6057/ |title=\u0414\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b \u0442\u044e\u0440\u044c\u043c\u0443 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0420\u044b\u0431\u043a\u0438: \u0434\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 |trans-title=Deripaska ordered a prison for Rybka: evidence |work=\u041d\u0430\u0432\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 (Navalny) |last=\u041d\u0430\u0432\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 |first=\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0439 (Navalny, Alexei) |author-link=Alexei Navalny |date=21 January 2019 |access-date=5 February 2020 |language=ru}}</ref>}} off the coast of Norway{{efn|During early August 2013, Deripaska and his yatch ''Elden'' stayed in the resort of Sj\u00f8garden at Flatset in [[Aver\u00f8y]] in [[Nordm\u00f8re]] [[Norway]].<ref name=E2406082013>{{cite news |url=https://e24.no/naeringsliv/i/y3952A/paa-norgesferie-med-to-jetfly-og-yacht-med-egen-foelgebaat |title=P\u00e5 norgesferie med to jetfly og yacht med egen f\u00f8lgeb\u00e5t: Se hvordan Russlands 16. rikeste mann ferierer p\u00e5 Nordm\u00f8re |trans-title=On a Norwegian holiday with two jets and a yacht with its own companion boat: See how Russia's 16th richest man is vacationing in North Morea |work=[[E24 N\u00e6ringsliv|E24]] |last=Utheim |first=Eric B. |date=6 August 2013 |access-date=5 February 2020 |language=no}}</ref><ref name=TidensKrau06082013>{{cite news |url=https://www.tk.no/nyheter/en-av-verdens-rikeste-ferierer-pa-nordmore/s/1-113-6794088 |title=En av verdens rikeste ferierer p\u00e5 Nordm\u00f8re |trans-title=One of the world's richest vacations on Nordm\u00f8re |work=[[Tidens Krav]] |location=[[Kristiansund]], [[Norway]] |last=Aln\u00e6s |first= Ole Knut |date=6 August 2013 |access-date=5 February 2020 |language=no}}</ref>}} with [[Sergei Eduardovich Prikhodko|Sergei Prikhodko]],{{efn|According to Navalny, many consider Prikhodko more influential on Russia foreign affairs than [[Sergei Lavrov]].<ref name=FBK08022018/>}} during September to October 2016 in [[southern Russia]] at Deripaska's mansion, and during January 2017 at [[Lech am Arlberg|Lech]], [[Austria]], with United States lobbyist Adam Waldman of the firm Endeavor Group.<ref name=Bell26012019>{{cite news |url=https://thebell.io/en/revelations-to-come-a-deep-dive-into-what-nastya-rybka-might-know/ |title=Revelations to come? A deep dive into what Nastya Rybka might know |work=[[:ru:The Bell|The Bell]] |last=Stognei |first=Anastasia |date=26 January 2019 |access-date=5 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> As of January 2019, Vashukevich has written three books about her relationship with Deripaska: ''Who Wants to Seduce a Billionaire'' ({{lang-ru|\u0414\u043d\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0441\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043c\u0438\u043b\u043b\u0438\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430, \u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043a\u043b\u043e\u043d \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043e\u043b\u0438\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0445\u0430}} ''lit.'' The Billionaire Seduction Diary, or Clone for the Oligarch) ({{ISBN|978-5-699-93242-9}}); ''Eurotrash, How to Seduce the Rich for the Poor'' ({{lang-ru|Eurotrash. \u0421\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0431\u043e\u0433\u0430\u0442\u044b\u0445 \u043d\u0430 \u0431\u0435\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0445}}); and a third unpublished book.<ref name=Bell26012019/>\n\nReleased in September 2017 in collaboration with Alex Lesley,{{efn|Anastasiya Vashukevich is also known as Nastya Rybka and Aleksandr Kirillov ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u041a\u0438\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043b\u043e\u0432}}; {{lang-be|\u0410\u043b\u044f\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u041a\u0456\u0440\u044b\u043b\u0430\u045e}}) is also known as Alex Lesley or Alex Leslie ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u041b\u0435\u0441\u043b\u0438}}) (b. 1982 [[Vitebsk]], [[Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic|Belorussian SSR]]).<ref name=EksmoLeslie>{{cite news |url=https://eksmo.ru/authors/lesli-aleks-ID8764/ |title=\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u041b\u0435\u0441\u043b\u0438 |trans-title=Alex Leslie |work=[[Eksmo]] |access-date=6 February 2020 |language=ru}}</ref><ref name=belsat22012019>{{cite web|url=https://belsat.eu/en/news/kremlin-escort-girl-at-liberty-lukashenka-gets-interested-in-case/|title=Kremlin escort girl at liberty. Lukashenka gets interested in case|author=|website=[[Belsat TV|belsat.eu]]|date=22 January 2019|access-date=22 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=BBC15012019>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/russian/news-46876837 |title=\u041d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044f \u0420\u044b\u0431\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u041b\u0435\u0441\u043b\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0443\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u0440\u043e\u043a \u0432 \u0422\u0430\u0438\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0435 |trans-title=Nastya Rybka and Alex Leslie received a suspended sentence in Thailand |work=[[BBC]] |date=19 January 2019 |access-date=7 February 2020 |language=ru}}</ref>}} Vashukevich's book ''Eurotrash, How to Seduce the Rich for the Poor'' details her trip to Lech, Austria, in early January 2017 with Oleg Deripaska to meet with Adam Waldman, who through Waldman's firm, Endeavor Group, has been a lobbyist for Deripaska since 2009{{efn|Adam Waldman through his Endeavor Group was hired as counsel for [[Russian Foreign Minister]] [[Sergei Lavrov]] in 2009-10 to help expedite [[Oleg Deripaska]] obtaining a United States visa to travel to the United States.<ref name=Guardian20062018>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2018/jun/20/us-lobbyist-for-russian-oligarch-visited-julian-assange-nine-times-last-year |title= US lobbyist for Russian oligarch visited Julian Assange nine times last year: It is unclear whether Adam Waldman's 2017 visits had connection to Oleg Deripaska |work=[[The Guardian]] |last1=Kirchgaessner |first1=Stephanie |last2=Harding |first2=Luke |author2-link=Luke Harding |date=20 June 2018 |access-date=5 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Many payments from Deripaska to Waldman went through numerous offshore shell companies including firms in Jersey, the British Virgin Islands, Belize and firms associated with anonymous ownership Cyprus firms such as the Sea Chaika Corporation, a Deripaska firm that appears in the [[Panama Papers]].<ref name=Guardian20062018/> In 2010, Carolyn Mansfield was a managing director of the Endeavor Group.<ref name=FARA05082009>{{cite web |url=https://efile.fara.gov/docs/5934-Supplemental-Statement-20100630-2.pdf |title=The Endeavor Law Firm, PC, FARA Registration |work=Department of Justice |date=31 May 2010 |access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref>}} and for [[Julian Assange]].{{efn|Adam Waldman visited the [[Embassy of Ecuador, London|Ecuadorian embassy in London]] to meet with Julian Assange nine times during 2017: 12, 13, and 27 January; twice in late March; three times in April; and twice at the end of November 2017.<ref name=Guardian20062018/>}} On 12-13 January 2017, Adam Waldman met with Julian Assange just days after Waldman's Lech, Austria, meeting in a bar at Deripaska's five star Aurelio Hotel with Deripaska and Vashukevich on 7 January 2017.<ref name=Guardian20062018/><ref name=Proekt11122018>{{cite news |url=https://www.proekt.media/article/adam-waldman/ |title=\u0410\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043b\u043e\u0431\u0431\u0438\u0441\u0442 \u0410\u0434\u0430\u043c \u0423\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043c\u0430\u043d \u0432\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0441\u044f \u0441 \u041e\u043b\u0435\u0433\u043e\u043c \u0414\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434 \u0432\u0438\u0437\u0438\u0442\u043e\u043c \u043a \u0414\u0436\u0443\u043b\u0438\u0430\u043d\u0443 \u0410\u0441\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0436\u0443 |trans-title=American lobbyist Adam Waldman met with Oleg Deripaska before a visit to Julian Assange |work=\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442 \u041c\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0430 (Proekt) |last= |first= |date=11 December 2018 |access-date=5 February 2020 |language=ru}}</ref> Vashukevich made a video recording with her phone of the 7 January 2017 meeting in the bar.<ref name=Proekt11122018/>\n\nIn her unpublished book, she describes a three day trip during the fall of 2016 to Deripaska's mansion near [[Krasnodar]] where an important-looking man arrived in an all terrain vehicle to discuss issues with Deripaska.<ref name=Bell26012019/> Vashukevich recorded these meetings with her phone hidden behind some books.<ref name=Bell26012019/>\n\nVashukevich said that she was close to [[Oleg Deripaska]],<ref name=Scandals21092017>{{cite news |url=https://scandaly.ru/2017/09/21/ryibka-poymala-v-seti-olega-deripasku/ |title=\u0420\u044b\u0431\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0439\u043c\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0432 \u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438 \u041e\u043b\u0435\u0433\u0430 \u0414\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u0441\u043a\u0443: \u0414\u0435\u0432\u0443\u0448\u043a\u0430, \u0437\u0430\u043d\u044f\u0432\u0448\u0430\u044f\u0441\u044f \u0441\u0435\u043a\u0441\u043e\u043c \u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0431\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439, \u043e\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c \u044d\u043a\u0441-\u043b\u044e\u0431\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0435\u0439 \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0446\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u00ab\u0411\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u044d\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u00bb (\u0444\u043e\u0442\u043e) |trans-title=Fish caught in the net of Oleg Deripaska: The girl who had sex on the embankment turned out to be the ex-lover of the owner of the Basic Element company (photo) |work=\u0441\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430\u043b\u044b.\u0440\u0443 |last= |first= |date=21 September 2017 |access-date=6 February 2020 |language=ru}}</ref> a Russian oligarch with ties to Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] and business links to [[Paul Manafort]]. She claimed the recorded voices included Deripaska's discussing the 2016 presidential election with other people, including at least three fluent English speakers who she believed were Americans.<ref name=CNN06032018>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/05/asia/thailand-sex-guru-deportation-russia-intl/index.html |title=Jailed Russian 'sex coaches' offer to trade election info for US asylum |work=[[CNN]] |last1=Watson |first1=Ivan |last2=Olarn |first2=Kocha |date=6 March 2018 |access-date=7 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>{{efn|During emails sent 29 and 31 July 2016, [[Konstantin Kilimnik]] and [[Paul Manafort]] decided to meet in New York City on 2 August 2016.<ref name=Atlantic02102017>{{cite news |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/10/emails-suggest-manafort-sought-approval-from-putin-ally-deripaska/541677/ |title=Did Manafort Use Trump to Curry Favor With a Putin Ally? Emails turned over to investigators detail the former campaign chair's efforts to please an oligarch tied to the Kremlin. |work=[[The Atlantic]] |last1=Ioffe |first1=Julia |last2=Foer |first2=Franklin |date=2 October 2017 |access-date=7 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> During the evening of the 2 August 2016 Manafort and Kilimnik meeting in the Grand Havana Club at [[Jared Kushner]] owned [[666 Fifth Avenue]],<ref name=Atlantic02102017/> M-ALAY flew from Moscow to [[Newark, New Jersey]], and after the Manafort-Kilimnik meeting it returned the next morning to Moscow on 3-4 August.<ref name=Medium06032018>{{cite news |url=https://medium.com/@ScottMStedman/deripaskas-private-jet-newark-moscow-molde-for-secret-yacht-meeting-280494a6cb48 |title=Deripaska\u2019s private jet: Newark-Moscow-Molde for secret yacht meeting. Konstantin Kilimnik, the Ukrainian political consultant who has ties to Russian intelligence, said the two discussed unpaid bills and current news. |work=[[Medium (website)|Medium]] |last=Stedman |first=Scott |date=6 March 2018 |access-date=7 February 2020 |language=en |archive-date=10 April 2018 |archive-url=https://archive.is/Ub4Fm}}</ref> It then flew to [[Molde Airport, \u00c5r\u00f8|Molde]], Norway, on 5 August 2016 while M-UGIC flew from [[Montenegro]] to Molde on 5 August 2016, also.<ref name=Medium06032018/> Navalny states that Deripaska flew on M-UGIC from Montenegro to Molde and Sergei Prikhodko flew on M-ALAY from Moscow to Molde.<ref name=FBK08022018/><ref name=Medium06032018/> Vashukevich believes that others were aboard the flights, too.<ref name=CNN01032018>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/02/28/asia/russia-model-thai-prison-trump-claims-intl/index.html |title=Russian model in Thai jail promises to spill Trump-Russia secrets |work=[[CNN]] |last=Burrows |first=Emma |date=1 March 2018 |access-date=7 February 2020}}</ref>}} On 8 February 2018, activist [[Alexei Navalny]] released a video<ref name=NavalnyVideoAug2016>{{cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RQZr2NgKPiU |title=\u042f\u0445\u0442\u044b, \u043e\u043b\u0438\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0445\u0438, \u0434\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0447\u043a\u0438: \u043e\u0445\u043e\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u043c\u0443\u0436\u0447\u0438\u043d \u0440\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0447\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0432\u0437\u044f\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 |trans-title=Yachts, oligarchs, girls: a hunter for men exposes a bribe taker |work=\u041d\u0430\u0432\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 (Navalny) |last=\u041d\u0430\u0432\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 |first=\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0439 (Navalny, Alexei) |author-link=Alexei Navalny |date=8 February 2018 |access-date=7 February 2018 |language=ru |archive-date=8 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180208094907/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RQZr2NgKPiU |quote=Important items in the Navalny video have English subtitles.}}</ref> using material obtained by Vashukevich about an August 2016 meeting between Deripaska and Deputy Prime Minister [[Sergei Eduardovich Prikhodko|Sergei Prikhodko]] in which United States and Russia foreign policy was discussed as well as Prikhodko's friend United States diplomat [[Victoria Nuland]] and the 2016 United States elections.<ref name=FBK08022018/><ref name=Guardian20062018/> In the video, Navalny claimed Deripaska probably served as a liaison between the Russian government and Manafort in connection with Russian interference efforts in United States elections.<ref name=Guardian20062018/><ref name=\"Paddock030518\"/> Navalny correlates Vashukevich's book ''Who Wants to Seduce a Billionaire'' to persons, settings, and events in the Vashukevich film.<ref name=FBK08022018/> In the video known as ''Fishgate'', ''Fish Gate'' or ''Rybka Gate'' ({{lang-ru|\u00ab\u0420\u044b\u0431\u043a\u0430-\u0433\u0435\u0439\u0442\u00bb}}), Navalny explains the characters and setting for Nastya Rybka's book ''Who Wants to Seduce a Billionaire'': ''Ruslan Zolotov'' is Deripaska, ''Papa'' is Prikhodko, ''Vitya'' or ''Victor'' is Yevgeny Agarkov and the Rybka book's setting of Greenland is actually Norway.<ref name=FBK08022018/><ref name=NavalnyRecordings21012019/> Rybka refers to Papa as [[Cardinal Richelieu|Richelieu]], or a Cardinal in the Kremlin who is the person actually responsible for Russia's foreign policy during the governments of [[Boris Yeltsin]], [[Vladimir Putin]], and [[Dmitri Medvedev]].<ref name=FBK08022018/><ref name=NavalnyRecordings21012019/> Through Adam Waldman,<ref name=Guardian20062018/> Deripaska has denied bribery allegations presented in the video.<ref name=\"dw.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/en/sex-power-politics-and-the-kremlin-nastya-rybka-case/a-47249326|title=Sex, power, politics, and the Kremlin: Nastya Rybka case |work=[[Deutsche Welle]] |date=26 January 2019 |access-date=5 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nDeripaska filed a lawsuit in Deripaska's hometown court at [[Ust-Labinsk]], [[Krasnodar Krai]], Russia, against Rybka and Leslie for publishing material about him.<ref name=1RBC26022018>{{cite news |url=https://www.rbc.ru/rbcfreenews/5a93cc879a794727c1e40562 |title=\u0412 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435 \u0441\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043e \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u0449\u0435\u0439 \u0434\u0435\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u041b\u0435\u0441\u043b\u0438 \u0438 \u0420\u044b\u0431\u043a\u0438 \u0438\u0437 \u0422\u0430\u0438\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430 |trans-title=The consulate announced the upcoming deportation of Leslie and Rybka from Thailand |work=[[RBK Group|RBC]] |date=26 February 2018 |access-date=7 February 2020 |language=ru}}</ref><ref name=Navalny10022019>{{cite news |url=https://navalny.com/p/5756/ |title=\u041d\u0430\u0448\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043e \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0440\u0443\u043f\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0437\u044f\u0445 \u0447\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u0445\u043e\u0434\u044c\u043a\u043e \u0438 \u043e\u043b\u0438\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0445\u0430 \u0414\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u043e\u0431\u044a\u044f\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043e \u00ab\u0437\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0449\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0435\u0439\u00bb |trans-title=Our investigation into corruption ties between official Prikhodko and oligarch Deripaska is declared \u201cforbidden information\u201d |work=\u041d\u0430\u0432\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 (Navalny) |last=\u041d\u0430\u0432\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 |first=\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0439 (Navalny, Alexei) |author-link=Alexei Navalny |date=10 February 2018 |access-date=7 February 2020 |language=ru}}</ref> On 10 February 2018, [[Roskomnadzor]] placed Navalny's website and his investigation video on the prohibited log.<ref name=1RBC26022018/><ref name=Navalny10022019/> On 24 February 2018, Navalny removed his investigation video from his website.<ref name=1RBC26022018/>\n\n=== Arrest in Thailand ===\nOn 25 February 2018, Vashukevich was arrested at a hotel in [[Pattaya]], [[Thailand]], and held at Nong Pla Lai Prison.<ref name=Bell26012019/><ref name=RFE26022018>{{cite news |url=https://www.rferl.org/a/thailand-woman-rybkagate-detained/29063099.html |title=Thailand Detains Woman At Center Of Navalny's 'Rybkagate' Report |work=[[Radio Free Europe]] |date=26 February 2018 |access-date=7 February 2020}}</ref> According to Vladimir Sosnov, the head of the consular department of the [[List of ambassadors of Russia to Thailand|Russian embassy in Thailand]], Rybka was one of ten Russian experts on lovemaking that were detained \"awaiting trial and deportation from Thailand.\"<ref name=CNN01032018/><ref name=RIAnovosti26022018>{{cite news |url=https://ria.ru/20180226/1515271223.html |title=\u0417\u0430\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0432 \u0422\u0430\u0438\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0435 \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432 \"\u0441\u0435\u043a\u0441-\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0430\" \u043e\u0436\u0438\u0434\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0434\u0435\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0432 \u0420\u0424 |trans-title=Detained in Thailand, participants in \"sex training\" expects deportation to the Russian Federation |work=[[RIA Novosti]] |date=26 February 2018 |access-date=7 February 2020 |language=ru}}</ref><ref name=2RBC26022018>{{cite news |url=https://www.rbc.ru/rbcfreenews/5a93bbb49a794714b7c3b362 |title=\u041f\u043e\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0441\u044c \u0432\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043e \u0437\u0430\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0441\u0435\u043a\u0441-\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0430 \u0441 \u041d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0439 \u0420\u044b\u0431\u043a\u043e\u0439 |trans-title=There was a video of the detention of sex training participants with Nastya Rybka |work=[[RBK Group|RBC]] |date=26 February 2018 |access-date=7 February 2020 |language=ru}}</ref> While in custody,<ref name=\"torontosun.com\"/> she reached out to the American government seeking asylum in exchange for photographs and 16 hours of audio recordings she made in August 2016, that could shed light on possible [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Russian interference in American elections]].<ref name=\"Paddock030518\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/05/world/asia/nastya-rybka-trump-putin.html|title=Escort Says Audio Recordings Show Russian Meddling in U.S. Election|first=Richard C.|last=Paddock|date=5 March 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=RadioSvoboda28022018>{{cite news |url=https://www.svoboda.org/a/29067518.html |title=\u0420\u044b\u0431\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u041b\u0435\u0441\u043b\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0443\u0431\u0435\u0436\u0438\u0449\u0430 \u0432 \u0421\u0428\u0410  |trans-title=Rybka and Leslie asked for political asylum in the United States |work=[[Radio Svoboda]] |date=February 28, 2018 |access-date=February 8, 2020 |language=ru}}</ref> She was visited by [[Federal Security Service|FSB]], [[CIA]], and many times by Vladimir Pronin, the [[Russia\u2013Thailand relations|Russia]] [[Consul (representative)|consul]] for the Pattaya [[consular district]], but the [[FBI]] was not allowed to visit because Thai officials only allowed visitors that were legal representatives for her and her family members.<ref name=Bell26012019/><ref name=CNN13032018>{{cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/03/13/asia/thai-russian-sex-coaches-lawyers-intl/index.html |title=FBI tried to contact 'sex coaches' in Thai jail |work=[[CNN]] |last1=Watson |first1=Ivan |last2=Olarn |first2=Kocha |date=13 March 2018 |access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref> According to Jillian Bonnardeaux spokesperson for the [[Embassy of the United States, Bangkok|United States embassy in Bangkok]], all matters involving asylum are directed to [[Kirstjen Nielsen]] and the [[United States Secretary of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]].<ref name=CNN06032018/>{{efn|On 28 February 2018, the [[Radio Free Europe]] website displayed photos of her asylum request that had been delivered to the United States embassy in Thailand by Ukrainian-American, Pavlo Yunko.<ref name=RadioSvoboda28022018/> The note signed by the ten persons detained by Thai authorities including Vashukevich stated that they had \"run out of Russia to Thailand\" because they had been \"repressed by Russia\" for the materials they had including \"photo-video-audio of crymes of Russian government\" ... \"about US Relations with russia\".<ref name=RadioSvoboda28022018/>}} Vladimir Pronin gained her release for time served if she left Thailand which she did and, according to court order, returned to Belarus.<ref name=NavalnyRecordings21012019/><ref name=Bell26012019/> According to Navalny, Deripaska wanted her to spend time in prison and had Tatyana Valerianovna Monegen ({{lang-ru|\u0422\u0430\u0442\u044c\u044f\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u041c\u043e\u043d\u044d\u0433\u044d\u043d}}) and George Oganov ({{lang-ru|\u0413\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0438\u0439 \u041e\u0433\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432}}) explain to an English-speaking attorney ''William'' that Deripaska was not happy with deportation but wanted prison for Vashukevich.<ref name=NavalnyRecordings21012019/>{{efn|Tatyana Valerianovna Monegen has been secretary general of the Russian branch of the [[International Chamber of Commerce]] (ICC) which Oleg Deripaska founded.<ref name=NavalnyRecordings21012019/> Both his [[Rusal]] and the Russian branch of ICC have the same phone number.<ref name=NavalnyRecordings21012019/> According to Nalvany, Tatyana Monegen assists Deripaska in finding escorts.<ref name=NavalnyRecordings21012019/> George Oganov is a former Russian diplomat who was press secretary for the Russian embassy in the United States and, as of 2019, is on the board of directors of [[Basic Element (company)|Basic Element]] and is an advisor to its president Oleg Deripaska.<ref name=NavalnyRecordings21012019/>}} Vashukevich believed that [[Nikolai Patrushev]] who had traveled to Thailand was involved.<ref name=CNN01032018/>{{efn|The [[Mueller Report]] was submitted to Barr on March 22, 2018, but no one interviewed Vashukevich during the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Muller Investigation]].}}\n\n=== Disruption to Russian websites ===\nSoon after Vashukevich was arrested, Navalny began posting more of her photographs on his website. The Russian internet agency [[Roskomnadzor]] restricted access to Navalny's website,<ref name=\"MacFarquhar_4/30/2018\">{{cite web | last=MacFarquhar | first=Neil | title='They Want to Block Our Future': Thousands Protest Russia's Internet Censorship | website=[[The New York Times]] | date=30 April 2018 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/30/world/europe/russia-telegram-digital-resistance.html | access-date=22 January 2019}}</ref> which was on the [[Telegram (software)|Telegram]] network, also blocking as many as 18 million other sites,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://index.qz.com/1256073/russia-internet-ban-blocks-telegram-and-millions-of-websites-including-google-and-amazon-ip-addresses/|title=Russia internet ban blocks Telegram and millions of websites, including Google and Amazon IP addresses \u2014 Quartz|author=|date=|website=index.qz.com|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> and triggering anti-censorship demonstrations against Putin.<ref name=\"MacFarquhar_4/30/2018\" />\n\n=== Relinquishment of recordings, apology ===\nIn August 2018, Vashukevich said she had sent the audio recordings to Deripaska without making them public, hoping he would be able to gain her release from prison.<ref>{{cite news|last=Paddock|first=Richard C.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/31/world/asia/escort-anastasia-vashukevich-nastya-rybka-trump.html|title=She Gambled on Her Claim to Link Russians and Trump. She Is Losing|work=The New York Times|date=31 August 2018|accessdate=31 August 2018}}</ref> She said she promised Deripaska she would not make any further comment on the recordings' contents.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kaewjinda|first=Kaweewit|url=http://time.com/5371527/thailand-russia-escort-anastasia-vashukevich/|title=Belarusian Escort Says She Made a Deal With an Oligarch to Keep Quiet About Russian Meddling|work=Time|agency=Associated Press|date=20 August 2018|access-date=31 August 2018}}</ref> In court, Vashukevich apologized to Deripaska and Prikhodko.<ref name=\"dw.com\"/>\n\nIn 2018, Deripaska won a legal case in Deripaska's hometown court at [[Ust-Labinsk]], [[Krasnodar Krai]], Russia, against Vashukevich for the invasion of his privacy by the public availability of videos and photos of the two of them together.<ref name=Proekt11122018/><ref>{{cite news|last=Maza|first=Cristina|url=https://www.newsweek.com/belarusian-escort-says-she-gave-evidence-russian-election-interference-1081677|title=Belarusian Escort Says She Gave Evidence of Russian Election Interference to Manafort-Linked Oligarch|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=20 August 2018|access-date=31 August 2018}}</ref> Deripaska sued for 1 million rubles from each Vashukevich and Kirillov but the court set the payment at 500,000 rubles for each Vashukevich and Kirillov.<ref name=Proekt11122018/><ref name=Life09062018>{{cite news |url=https://life.ru/p/1133184 |title=\u0414\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u043e\u0442\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0438\u043b \u043f\u043e \u043f\u043e\u043b\u043c\u0438\u043b\u043b\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0440\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0435\u0439 \u0443 \u041d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0420\u044b\u0431\u043a\u0438 \u0438 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430 \u041b\u0435\u0441\u043b\u0438: \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043f\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u0440\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0438\u043b \u0441\u0443\u0434 \u0432\u0437\u044b\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0442\u044c \u043f\u043e \u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u043c\u0438\u043b\u043b\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0443 \u0440\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0435\u0439 \u0441 \u043a\u0430\u0436\u0434\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a\u0430. |trans-title=Deripaska seized half a million rubles from Nastya Rybka and Alex Leslie: The entrepreneur had previously requested the court to recover one million rubles from each defendant. |agency=[[Life (news agency, Russia)|Life]] |last=\u0424\u0451\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432 |first=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 (Fedorov, Vladislav) |date=8 June 2018 |access-date=6 February 2020 |language=ru}}</ref>\n\n==Arrest and release==\nVashukevich was arrested at [[Sheremetyevo International Airport|Sheremetyevo Airport]] [[Moscow]] in January 2019 while in transit from Thailand to Belarus for reportedly drawing people into prostitution.<ref name=belsat22012019/><ref name=Bell19012019>{{cite news |url=https://thebell.io/en/deportation-detention-and-up-to-8-years-prison-the-latest-on-nastya-rybka/ |title=Deportation, detention and up to 8 years prison: the latest on Nastya Rybka |work=[[:ru:The Bell|The Bell]] |last=Stognei |first=Anastasia |date=19 January 2019 |access-date=5 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> After videos showing her being violently arrested and pleading for her life in court were leaked to the press, [[President of Belarus|Belarusian President]] [[Alexander Lukashenko]] demanded her release.<ref name=belsat22012019/> She was immediately released.<ref>{{cite news |title=Russia Frees Model who Claimed Trump Secrets from Police Custody |author= |url=https://themoscowtimes.com/news/russia-frees-model-from-police-custody-who-claimed-trump-secrets-64243 |newspaper=[[The Moscow Times]] |date=22 January 2019 |access-date=22 January 2019}}</ref> Vashukevich said she was warned not to discuss Deripaska while in Russian custody. She said her claims about him were intended to save her from death while detained in Thailand.<ref name=\"cnn.com\"/>\n\nSince her release, she has stated that she wants to have an appointment in person with Belarus president Lukashenko so that someday she could be elected a deputy in her hometown Babruysk.<ref name=Scandals14112019>{{cite news |url=https://scandaly.ru/2019/11/14/nastya-ryibka-stanet-deputatom-i-otomstit-deripaske/ |title=\u041d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044f \u0420\u044b\u0431\u043a\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0442 \u0434\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043c \u0438 \u043e\u0442\u043e\u043c\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442 \u0414\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u0441\u043a\u0435?: \u041a\u0430\u043a \u0436\u0438\u0432\u0443\u0442 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435 \u0433\u0440\u043e\u043c\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0441\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0438 \u043e\u0442\u0441\u0438\u0434\u043a\u0438 \u0432 \u0442\u0430\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0442\u044e\u0440\u044c\u043c\u0435 \u044d\u043a\u0441-\u043f\u043e\u0434\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0430 \u043e\u043b\u0438\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0445\u0430 \u0438 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u041b\u0435\u0441\u043b\u0438 |trans-title=Nastya Rybka will become a deputy and take revenge on Deripaska? How the ex-girlfriend of the oligarch and Alex Leslie live after a scandal and a jail in a Thai prison |work=\u0441\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430\u043b\u044b.\u0440\u0443 |last= |first= |date=14 November 2019 |access-date=6 February 2020 |language=ru}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBorn Anastasia Kostina ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0438\u044f \u041a\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430}}; {{lang-be|\u041d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0441\u044f \u041a\u043e\u0441\u0446\u0456\u043d\u0430}}) on 27 February 1990 in [[Babruysk]], [[Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic|Byelorussian SSR]], when her mother, a well-known [[ophthalmologist]], was forty.<ref name=Gomel>{{cite news |url=https://sozh.info/nastya-rybka-shkolnaya-zhizn-byvshie-muzhya-i-broshennyjj-syn/ |title=\u041d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044f \u0420\u044b\u0431\u043a\u0430: \u0448\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0436\u0438\u0437\u043d\u044c, \u0431\u044b\u0432\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u043c\u0443\u0436\u044c\u044f \u0438 \u0431\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u044b\u043d |trans-title=Nastya Rybka: school life, ex-husbands and abandoned son |work=\u041d\u0430\u0448 \u0413\u043e\u043c\u0435\u043b\u044c (Our Gomel)| date=14 February 2018 |access-date=6 February 2020 |language=ru}}</ref><ref name=ProGomel14022018>{{cite news |url=https://progomel.by/society/people/2018/02/33457.html |title=\u041e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u043a\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u0441\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u041d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0420\u044b\u0431\u043a\u0438: \u0420\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0440\u0430\u0442 \u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u0441\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u0413\u043e\u043c\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0449\u0438\u043d\u0435, \u043a\u043e\u0433\u0434\u0430 \u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0438\u0437\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u043c\u0443\u0436\u0443 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0435\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0432 \u041c\u043e\u0437\u044b\u0440\u0435 (\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043e): \u0418\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0438\u043c\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u0440\u043e\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u0438 \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f\u043c\u0438 \u041d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044f \u0420\u044b\u0431\u043a\u0430 \u043e\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c \u0434\u0435\u0432\u0443\u0448\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0441 \u0432\u044b\u0441\u0448\u0438\u043c \u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435\u043c \u0438 \u0434\u0432\u0443\u043c\u044f \u0431\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u0437\u0430 \u043f\u043b\u0435\u0447\u0430\u043c\u0438. |trans-title=Classmate of the scandalous Nastya Rybka: Debauchery began in the Gomel region when she cheated on her husband at a session in Mozyr (video): Known for her provocative videos and statements, Nastya Rybka turned out to be a girl with a higher education and two marriages behind her. |work=ProGomel.by |last=\"\u0420\u0438\u0434\u0443\u0441\" (Reedus) |first= |date=14 February 2018 |access-date=6 February 2020 |language=ru}}</ref> She has no siblings.<ref name=ProGomel14022018/>\n\nShe attended night school after being expelled from school in ninth grade.<ref name=ProGomel14022018/> She became pregnant when she was 16 and married to become Anastasia Semenchuk ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0438\u044f \u0421\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0447\u0443\u043a}}; {{lang-be|\u0410\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0456\u044f \u0421\u0435\u043c\u044f\u043d\u0447\u0443\u043a}}).<ref name=ProGomel14022018/> She had a son Yury ({{lang-ru|\u042e\u0440\u0438\u0439}}).<ref name=ProGomel14022018/> She attended the institute in Belarus [[Mazyr]] and received an environmental degree in absentia.<ref name=ProGomel14022018/> She was 18 when she started a romance on the side; later, she divorced.<ref name=ProGomel14022018/>\n\nHer second marriage was to Nikolai Vashukevich ({{lang-ru|\u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u044f \u0412\u0430\u0448\u0443\u043a\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447}}; {{lang-be|\u041c\u0456\u043a\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0439 \u0412\u0430\u0448\u0443\u043a\u0435\u0432\u0456\u0447}}) but she left him and the son Yuri when Yuri was 11 for [[Moscow]].<ref name=ProGomel14022018/> Upon her return to Moscow in January 2019, Nikolai Vashukevich filmed the extremely rough treatment and arrest of Anastasia Vashukevich by Moscow police at the Sheremetyevo International Airport.<ref name=Bell19012019/>\n\n[[Kseniya Sobchak]] has publicly defended Anastaia Vashukevich.<ref name=TSN18022018>{{cite news |url=https://tsn.ua/svit/pornoskandal-v-otochenni-putina-hto-taka-nastya-ribka-i-chomu-nervuyut-u-kremli-1111653.html |title=\u041f\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430\u043b \u0432 \u043e\u0442\u043e\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0456 \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0456\u043d\u0430. \u0425\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u0430 \u041d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044f \u0420\u0438\u0431\u043a\u0430 \u0456 \u0447\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u043d\u0435\u0440\u0432\u0443\u044e\u0442\u044c \u0443 \u041a\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043b\u0456 |trans-title=Porn scandal surrounding Putin. Who is Nastya Rybka and why are they nervous in the Kremlin |work=[[:uk:\u0422\u0421\u041d#\u0422\u0421\u041d \u0432 \u0406\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0435\u0442\u0456|TSN]] |date=18 February 2018 |access-date=6 February 2020 |language=uk}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* Rybka, Nastya. [https://eksmo.ru/book/dnevnik-po-soblazneniyu-milliardera-ili-klon-dlya-oligarkha-ITD833431/ ''Who Wants to Seduce a Billionaire'' (\u0414\u043d\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0441\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043c\u0438\u043b\u043b\u0438\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430, \u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043a\u043b\u043e\u043d \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043e\u043b\u0438\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0445\u0430 ''lit.'' The Billionaire Seduction Diary, or Clone for the Oligarch)]. Moscow. [[Eksmo]], 2017. {{ISBN|978-5-699-93242-9}} \n* Leslie, Alex; Rybka, Nastya. ''Eurotrash, How to Seduce the Rich for the Poor'' ({{lang-ru|Eurotrash. \u0421\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0431\u043e\u0433\u0430\u0442\u044b\u0445 \u043d\u0430 \u0431\u0435\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0445}}). Moscow. [[Eksmo]], 2017. First published: September 5, 2017.\n* She recorded two songs.<ref name=Scandals14112019/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vashukevich, Anastasia}}\n[[Category:Belarusian bloggers]]\n[[Category:Belarusian female models]]\n[[Category:Escorts]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Prostitution in Belarus]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUS election related photographs, video, and audio recordings:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: three day \u2192 three-day", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anastasia_Vashukevich"}
{"title_page": "Cal Nichols", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Cal Nichols {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|CM}}\n| image       = Cal Nichols in 2006.png\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Cal Nichols at an Edmonton Oilers Community Appreciation event, 2006\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth based on age as of date|63|2005|10|2}}\n| birth_place = [[Paradise Hill, Saskatchewan|Paradise Hill]], [[Saskatchewan]], Canada\n| death_date  = \n| death_place =\n| death_cause = \n| nationality = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = Former chairman of the [[Edmonton Investors Group]] (EIG) that owned the Edmonton Oilers from 1998 to 2007\n| occupation  = Businessman\n}}\n'''Cal Nichols''' {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|CM}} (born c. 1942) is a Canadian businessman who spearheaded the group which would later become the [[Edmonton Investors Group]] (EIG) which owned the [[National Hockey League]]'s [[Edmonton Oilers]].<ref name=\"Group\">{{cite web|url=https://edmontonjournal.com/sports/hockey/nhl/cult-of-hockey/how-citizen-cal-nichols-saved-nhl-hockey-in-edmonton|title=How Citizen Cal Nichols saved NHL hockey in Edmonton 14 December 2007|last=|first=|date=|website=Edmonton Journal|publisher=|access-date=14 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in Paradise Hill, Saskatchewan, Nichols started his business career in 1962 as a 19 year old when his father cosigned papers for him to take over a rundown St Walburg Esso station. He worked hard to win the custom of the local farmers and also became involved in the local community playing sport and being elected as a Councillor at 23. He married Edna, a St Walburg girl and after 7 years in 1969, they moved to Edmonton.<ref name=\"Group\" />\n\nOver the next thirteen years he pursued various business and career opportunities. He was the commission bulk agent for Esso in Edmonton from 1972 through 1981, and served as Chairman of the Esso Agents Prairie Region Advisory Board. During his tenure, this became the largest Esso Agency in Canada. In 1983, anticipating the de-regulation of the crude oil and natural gas markets, Nichols and two associates founded Northridge Canada Inc. which became Canada's largest privately held crude oil and natural gas trading company. Northridge was ultimately sold to [[TC PipeLines|TransCanada Pipelines]]. In 1985, he created Gasland Oil, with its head office in Edmonton. Gasland grew to have over 50 branded petroleum outlets in Western Canada, many with convenience stores and other customer facilities. He sold substantially all of Gasland's petroleum marketing business in 1996 to [[Husky Energy]], but retained Gasland Properties Ltd., he has therefore shifted his focus to developing that company's various holdings.<ref name=\"Group\" />\n\nIn May 2002, he was inducted into the Alberta Business Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gasland.com/cal-nichols.php|title=Profile of Cal Nichols, C.M.|last=|first=|date=|website=Gasland Properties Ltd|publisher=|access-date=14 October 2016}}</ref>  He was awarded the Queens Golden Julnilee Medal  <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gg.ca/honour.aspx?id=4150&t=6&ln=Nichols|title=Golden Jubilee Medal|last=|first=|date=|website=The Governor General of Canada|publisher=|access-date=14 October 2016}}</ref> created in 2002 to commemorate the 50th anniversary to Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II to the throne and awarded to persons who had made outstanding contributions to both their own community and to Canada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.gg.ca/honours/medals/hon04-qegj_e.asp|title=Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal|last=|first=|date=|website=Honours|publisher=|access-date=14 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, he was named to the [[Order of Canada]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/nichols-bandura-named-to-the-order-of-canada|title=Nichols, Bandura named to the Order of Canada 28 December 2014|last=|first=|date=|website=Edmonton Journal|publisher=|access-date=10 October 2016}}</ref> which was established in 1967 to acknowledge citizens who have \"...{{nbsp}}outstanding achievement, dedication to the community and service to the nation.\"  He was appointed a Member (C.M.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=15922|title=Order of Canada Appointments 26 December 2014|last=|first=|date=|website=The Governor General of Canada|publisher=|access-date=10 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nNicols summed up his own life view as [[Reciprocity (social and political philosophy)|reciprocity]]\n\n<blockquote>I believe in being rewarded for superior effort, harder work, ... you should benefit from that, but in the process of benefiting, you should never forget where you came from, and how can I use my good fortune to help those who are less fortunate. I think it\u2019s about living life in balance.<ref name=\"Group\" /></blockquote>\n\n==Edmonton Investors Group (EIG)==\nNichols had played hockey and was a season-ticket holder of the [[Edmonton Oilers|Oilers]] hockey team in [[Edmonton]].  The Oilers were owned [[Peter Pocklington]], who decisions regarding the team had disillusioned fans including a threat to move the team to the United States. In 1994 in return for taxpayer funds being used to refurbish the home ground [[Peter Pocklington|Pocklington]] had agreed that local buyers would be given the right to purchase the team for cnd$100 before he could sell it to an American buyer.  The [[Edmonton Oilers|Oilers]] were in financial difficulties but could receive league assistance if they could sell 13,000 seasons tickets and 90 percent of corporate boxes. In 1996, Nichols co-chaired the Friends of the Oilers (FOTO) ticket drive campaign and mainly through his efforts the 13,000 season tickets deadline was reached.  In 1997, when the franchise was put up for sale, he  spearheaded the bid from a local ownership group EIG made up of 37/38 investors by co-ordinating raising the $60 million in equity required to purchase the team. His motivation for this was to see the team remain [[Edmonton]] remain as a \"Major League City.\"  He started his tenure as chairman of the EIG board in March 2000.<ref name=\"Group\" />\n\nThe Oilers became financially successful with Forbes valuing the club at US$146 million.<ref name=\":0\" />  The success of the Oilers brought a  [[United States dollar|US$]]145 million offer from local [[billionaire]] [[Daryl Katz]] for the franchise, although Nichols subsequently said the team was not for sale. [[Daryl Katz]] upped the offer to [[United States dollar|US$]]150 million, but was turned down again.\n\nOn August 7, Katz made a third offer for the team of [[United States dollar|US$]]170 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/daryl-katz-explains-bid-to-buy-oilers-1.638075|title=Daryl Katz explains bid to buy Oilers|last=|first=|date=|website=CBS Sports|publisher=|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref> Nichols said the attempts to buy the team have caused \"[[collateral damage]]\" and he hoped the outright refusal brings closure to a vocal debate that has divided the group and the wider community since Katz's first offer.  Nichols was quoted as saying \"This is not about dollars. This is about [[Edmonton]]. An ownership group is best-suited for [[Edmonton]] and the [[Edmonton Oilers|Oilers]].\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/oilers-owners-reject-latest-purchase-offer/article1079854/|title=Oilers owners reject latest purchase offer  7 August 2007/updated 3 April 2000|last=|first=|date=|website=The Globe and Mail|publisher=|author=|accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn December 13, 2007, Katz submitted a fourth formal offer to EIG to buy the franchise. The offer was $188 million to the EIG shareholders, plus another $100 million towards the building of a new arena in downtown [[Edmonton]]. The offer was accepted and Nichols resigned as [[chairman of the board]] of directors for the EIG in December 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmontonsun.com/2014/12/26/ex-oiler-brass-honoured|title=Ex-Oiler brass honoured|last=|first=|date=|website=New Edmonton|publisher=|author=|accessdate=15 October 2016}}</ref>  and the 34 members of the EIG were paid out .<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/insight/from-the-archives-in-june-2008-daryl-katz-buys-the-edmonton-oilers|title=From the archives : in June 2008 Daryl Katz buys the Edmonton Oilers|last=|first=|date=|website=Edmonton Journal|publisher=|accessdate=15 October 2016}}</ref> Katz acknowledged the role of Niicols in the Oilers success, \"If it wasn\u2019t for Cal, the Oilers wouldn\u2019t be in Edmonton.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Alberta Enterprise Group ==\nIn 2007 Nichols banded together with a group of businessmen to form the [[Alberta Enterprise Group]]. Their purpose was to connect business leaders with Alberta policymaker and the public for the benefit of all stakeholders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://albertaenterprisegroup.com/about/|title=The History of the Alberta Enterprise Group|last=|first=|date=|website=Alberta Enterprise Group|publisher=|access-date=10 October 2016}}</ref> Nichols was Chairman and in November 2011 a new Chairman and Board were elected and he became Chairman [[Emeritus]], an honorary title. He was thanked for \"...{{nbsp}}his vision and leadership in helping to create this organization.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://albertaenterprisegroup.com/alberta-enterprise-group-elects-new-leadership/|title=Alberta Enterprise Group elects new leadership 18 November 2011|last=|first=|date=|website=Alberta Enterprise Group|publisher=|access-date=10 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Norris, Cal}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:Canadian sports businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Edmonton Oilers executives]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League executives]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Cal Nichols {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|CM}}\n| image       = Cal Nichols in 2006.png\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Cal Nichols at an Edmonton Oilers Community Appreciation event, 2006\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth based on age as of date|63|2005|10|2}}\n| birth_place = [[Paradise Hill, Saskatchewan|Paradise Hill]], [[Saskatchewan]], Canada\n| death_date  = \n| death_place =\n| death_cause = \n| nationality = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = Former chairman of the [[Edmonton Investors Group]] (EIG) that owned the Edmonton Oilers from 1998 to 2007\n| occupation  = Businessman\n}}\n'''Cal Nichols''' {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|CM}} (born c. 1942) is a Canadian businessman who spearheaded the group which would later become the [[Edmonton Investors Group]] (EIG) which owned the [[National Hockey League]]'s [[Edmonton Oilers]].<ref name=\"Group\">{{cite web|url=https://edmontonjournal.com/sports/hockey/nhl/cult-of-hockey/how-citizen-cal-nichols-saved-nhl-hockey-in-edmonton|title=How Citizen Cal Nichols saved NHL hockey in Edmonton 14 December 2007|last=|first=|date=|website=Edmonton Journal|publisher=|access-date=14 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in Paradise Hill, Saskatchewan, Nichols started his business career in 1962 as a 19 year old when his father cosigned papers for him to take over a rundown St Walburg Esso station. He worked hard to win the custom of the local farmers and also became involved in the local community playing sport and being elected as a Councillor at 23. He married Edna, a St Walburg girl and after 7 years in 1969, they moved to Edmonton.<ref name=\"Group\" />\n\nOver the next thirteen years he pursued various business and career opportunities. He was the commission bulk agent for Esso in Edmonton from 1972 through 1981, and served as Chairman of the Esso Agents Prairie Region Advisory Board. During his tenure, this became the largest Esso Agency in Canada. In 1983, anticipating the de-regulation of the crude oil and natural gas markets, Nichols and two associates founded Northridge Canada Inc. which became Canada's largest privately held crude oil and natural gas trading company. Northridge was ultimately sold to [[TC PipeLines|TransCanada Pipelines]]. In 1985, he created Gasland Oil, with its head office in Edmonton. Gasland grew to have over 50 branded petroleum outlets in Western Canada, many with convenience stores and other customer facilities. He sold substantially all of Gasland's petroleum marketing business in 1996 to [[Husky Energy]], but retained Gasland Properties Ltd., he has therefore shifted his focus to developing that company's various holdings.<ref name=\"Group\" />\n\nIn May 2002, he was inducted into the Alberta Business Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gasland.com/cal-nichols.php|title=Profile of Cal Nichols, C.M.|last=|first=|date=|website=Gasland Properties Ltd|publisher=|access-date=14 October 2016}}</ref>  He was awarded the Queens Golden Julnilee Medal  <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gg.ca/honour.aspx?id=4150&t=6&ln=Nichols|title=Golden Jubilee Medal|last=|first=|date=|website=The Governor General of Canada|publisher=|access-date=14 October 2016}}</ref> created in 2002 to commemorate the 50th anniversary to Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II to the throne and awarded to persons who had made outstanding contributions to both their own community and to Canada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.gg.ca/honours/medals/hon04-qegj_e.asp|title=Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal|last=|first=|date=|website=Honours|publisher=|access-date=14 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, he was named to the [[Order of Canada]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/nichols-bandura-named-to-the-order-of-canada|title=Nichols, Bandura named to the Order of Canada 28 December 2014|last=|first=|date=|website=Edmonton Journal|publisher=|access-date=10 October 2016}}</ref> which was established in 1967 to acknowledge citizens who have \"...{{nbsp}}outstanding achievement, dedication to the community and service to the nation.\"  He was appointed a Member (C.M.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=15922|title=Order of Canada Appointments 26 December 2014|last=|first=|date=|website=The Governor General of Canada|publisher=|access-date=10 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nNicols summed up his own life view as [[Reciprocity (social and political philosophy)|reciprocity]]\n\n<blockquote>I believe in being rewarded for superior effort, harder work, ... you should benefit from that, but in the process of benefiting, you should never forget where you came from, and how can I use my good fortune to help those who are less fortunate. I think it\u2019s about living life in balance.<ref name=\"Group\" /></blockquote>\n\n==Edmonton Investors Group (EIG)==\nNichols had played hockey and was a season-ticket holder of the [[Edmonton Oilers|Oilers]] hockey team in [[Edmonton]].  The Oliers were owned [[Peter Pocklington]], who decisions regarding the team had disillusioned fans including a threat to move the team to the United States. In 1994 in return for taxpayer funds being used to refurbish the home ground [[Peter Pocklington|Pocklington]] had agreed that local buyers would be given the right to purchase the team for cnd$100 before he could sell it to an American buyer.  The [[Edmonton Oilers|Oilers]] were in financial difficulties but could receive league assistance if they could sell 13,000 seasons tickets and 90 percent of corporate boxes. In 1996, Nichols co-chaired the Friends of the Oilers (FOTO) ticket drive campaign and mainly through his efforts the 13,000 season tickets deadline was reached.  In 1997, when the franchise was put up for sale, he  spearheaded the bid from a local ownership group EIG made up of 37/38 investors by co-ordinating raising the $60 million in equity required to purchase the team. His motivation for this was to see the team remain [[Edmonton]] remain as a \"Major League City.\"  He started his tenure as chairman of the EIG board in March 2000.<ref name=\"Group\" />\n\nThe Oilers became financially successful with Forbes valuing the club at US$146 million.<ref name=\":0\" />  The success of the Oilers brought a  [[United States dollar|US$]]145 million offer from local [[billionaire]] [[Daryl Katz]] for the franchise, although Nichols subsequently said the team was not for sale. [[Daryl Katz]] upped the offer to [[United States dollar|US$]]150 million, but was turned down again.\n\nOn August 7, Katz made a third offer for the team of [[United States dollar|US$]]170 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/daryl-katz-explains-bid-to-buy-oilers-1.638075|title=Daryl Katz explains bid to buy Oilers|last=|first=|date=|website=CBS Sports|publisher=|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref> Nichols said the attempts to buy the team have caused \"[[collateral damage]]\" and he hoped the outright refusal brings closure to a vocal debate that has divided the group and the wider community since Katz's first offer.  Nichols was quoted as saying \"This is not about dollars. This is about [[Edmonton]]. An ownership group is best-suited for [[Edmonton]] and the [[Edmonton Oilers|Oilers]].\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/oilers-owners-reject-latest-purchase-offer/article1079854/|title=Oilers owners reject latest purchase offer  7 August 2007/updated 3 April 2000|last=|first=|date=|website=The Globe and Mail|publisher=|author=|accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn December 13, 2007, Katz submitted a fourth formal offer to EIG to buy the franchise. The offer was $188 million to the EIG shareholders, plus another $100 million towards the building of a new arena in downtown [[Edmonton]]. The offer was accepted and Nichols resigned as [[chairman of the board]] of directors for the EIG in December 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmontonsun.com/2014/12/26/ex-oiler-brass-honoured|title=Ex-Oiler brass honoured|last=|first=|date=|website=New Edmonton|publisher=|author=|accessdate=15 October 2016}}</ref>  and the 34 members of the EIG were paid out .<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/insight/from-the-archives-in-june-2008-daryl-katz-buys-the-edmonton-oilers|title=From the archives : in June 2008 Daryl Katz buys the Edmonton Oilers|last=|first=|date=|website=Edmonton Journal|publisher=|accessdate=15 October 2016}}</ref> Katz acknowledged the role of Niicols in the Oilers success, \"If it wasn\u2019t for Cal, the Oilers wouldn\u2019t be in Edmonton.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Alberta Enterprise Group ==\nIn 2007 Nichols banded together with a group of businessmen to form the [[Alberta Enterprise Group]]. Their purpose was to connect business leaders with Alberta policymaker and the public for the benefit of all stakeholders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://albertaenterprisegroup.com/about/|title=The History of the Alberta Enterprise Group|last=|first=|date=|website=Alberta Enterprise Group|publisher=|access-date=10 October 2016}}</ref> Nichols was Chairman and in November 2011 a new Chairman and Board were elected and he became Chairman [[Emeritus]], an honorary title. He was thanked for \"...{{nbsp}}his vision and leadership in helping to create this organization.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://albertaenterprisegroup.com/alberta-enterprise-group-elects-new-leadership/|title=Alberta Enterprise Group elects new leadership 18 November 2011|last=|first=|date=|website=Alberta Enterprise Group|publisher=|access-date=10 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Norris, Cal}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:Canadian sports businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Edmonton Oilers executives]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League executives]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cal_Nichols"}
